141 /// The collection of all-type qualifiers we support.
142 /// Clang supports five independent qualifiers:
143 /// * C99: const, volatile, and restrict
144 /// * MS: __unaligned
145 /// * Embedded C (TR18037): address spaces
146 /// * Objective C: the GC attributes (none, weak, or strong)
147 class Qualifiers {
148 public:
149  enum TQ { // NOTE: These flags must be kept in sync with DeclSpec::TQ.
150  Const = 0x1,
151  Restrict = 0x2,
152  Volatile = 0x4,
153  CVRMask = Const | Volatile | Restrict
154  };
155 
156  enum GC {
157  GCNone = 0,
158  Weak,
159  Strong
160  };
161 
162  enum ObjCLifetime {
163  /// There is no lifetime qualification on this type.
164  OCL_None,
165 
166  /// This object can be modified without requiring retains or
167  /// releases.
168  OCL_ExplicitNone,
169 
170  /// Assigning into this object requires the old value to be
171  /// released and the new value to be retained. The timing of the
172  /// release of the old value is inexact: it may be moved to
173  /// immediately after the last known point where the value is
174  /// live.
175  OCL_Strong,
176 
177  /// Reading or writing from this object requires a barrier call.
178  OCL_Weak,
179 
180  /// Assigning into this object requires a lifetime extension.
181  OCL_Autoreleasing
182  };
183 
184  enum {
185  /// The maximum supported address space number.
186  /// 23 bits should be enough for anyone.
187  MaxAddressSpace = 0x7fffffu,
188 
189  /// The width of the "fast" qualifier mask.
190  FastWidth = 3,
191 
192  /// The fast qualifier mask.
193  FastMask = (1 << FastWidth) - 1
194  };
195 
196  /// Returns the common set of qualifiers while removing them from
197  /// the given sets.
198  static Qualifiers removeCommonQualifiers(Qualifiers &L, Qualifiers &R) {
199  // If both are only CVR-qualified, bit operations are sufficient.
200  if (!(L.Mask & ~CVRMask) && !(R.Mask & ~CVRMask)) {
201  Qualifiers Q;
202  Q.Mask = L.Mask & R.Mask;
203  L.Mask &= ~Q.Mask;
204  R.Mask &= ~Q.Mask;
205  return Q;
206  }
207 
208  Qualifiers Q;
209  unsigned CommonCRV = L.getCVRQualifiers() & R.getCVRQualifiers();
210  Q.addCVRQualifiers(CommonCRV);
211  L.removeCVRQualifiers(CommonCRV);
212  R.removeCVRQualifiers(CommonCRV);
213 
214  if (L.getObjCGCAttr() == R.getObjCGCAttr()) {
215  Q.setObjCGCAttr(L.getObjCGCAttr());
216  L.removeObjCGCAttr();
217  R.removeObjCGCAttr();
218  }
219 
220  if (L.getObjCLifetime() == R.getObjCLifetime()) {
221  Q.setObjCLifetime(L.getObjCLifetime());
222  L.removeObjCLifetime();
223  R.removeObjCLifetime();
224  }
225 
226  if (L.getAddressSpace() == R.getAddressSpace()) {
227  Q.setAddressSpace(L.getAddressSpace());
228  L.removeAddressSpace();
229  R.removeAddressSpace();
230  }
231  return Q;
232  }
233 
234  static Qualifiers fromFastMask(unsigned Mask) {
235  Qualifiers Qs;
236  Qs.addFastQualifiers(Mask);
237  return Qs;
238  }
239 
240  static Qualifiers fromCVRMask(unsigned CVR) {
241  Qualifiers Qs;
242  Qs.addCVRQualifiers(CVR);
243  return Qs;
244  }
245 
246  static Qualifiers fromCVRUMask(unsigned CVRU) {
247  Qualifiers Qs;
248  Qs.addCVRUQualifiers(CVRU);
249  return Qs;
250  }
251 
252  // Deserialize qualifiers from an opaque representation.
253  static Qualifiers fromOpaqueValue(unsigned opaque) {
254  Qualifiers Qs;
255  Qs.Mask = opaque;
256  return Qs;
257  }
258 
259  // Serialize these qualifiers into an opaque representation.
260  unsigned getAsOpaqueValue() const {
261  return Mask;
262  }
263 
264  bool hasConst() const { return Mask & Const; }
265  bool hasOnlyConst() const { return Mask == Const; }
266  void removeConst() { Mask &= ~Const; }
267  void addConst() { Mask |= Const; }
268 
269  bool hasVolatile() const { return Mask & Volatile; }
270  bool hasOnlyVolatile() const { return Mask == Volatile; }
271  void removeVolatile() { Mask &= ~Volatile; }
272  void addVolatile() { Mask |= Volatile; }
273 
274  bool hasRestrict() const { return Mask & Restrict; }
275  bool hasOnlyRestrict() const { return Mask == Restrict; }
276  void removeRestrict() { Mask &= ~Restrict; }
277  void addRestrict() { Mask |= Restrict; }
278 
279  bool hasCVRQualifiers() const { return getCVRQualifiers(); }
280  unsigned getCVRQualifiers() const { return Mask & CVRMask; }
281  unsigned getCVRUQualifiers() const { return Mask & (CVRMask | UMask); }
282 
283  void setCVRQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
284  assert(!(mask & ~CVRMask) && "bitmask contains non-CVR bits");
285  Mask = (Mask & ~CVRMask) | mask;
286  }
287  void removeCVRQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
288  assert(!(mask & ~CVRMask) && "bitmask contains non-CVR bits");
289  Mask &= ~mask;
290  }
291  void removeCVRQualifiers() {
292  removeCVRQualifiers(CVRMask);
293  }
294  void addCVRQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
295  assert(!(mask & ~CVRMask) && "bitmask contains non-CVR bits");
296  Mask |= mask;
297  }
298  void addCVRUQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
299  assert(!(mask & ~CVRMask & ~UMask) && "bitmask contains non-CVRU bits");
300  Mask |= mask;
301  }
302 
303  bool hasUnaligned() const { return Mask & UMask; }
304  void setUnaligned(bool flag) {
305  Mask = (Mask & ~UMask) | (flag ? UMask : 0);
306  }
307  void removeUnaligned() { Mask &= ~UMask; }
308  void addUnaligned() { Mask |= UMask; }
309 
310  bool hasObjCGCAttr() const { return Mask & GCAttrMask; }
311  GC getObjCGCAttr() const { return GC((Mask & GCAttrMask) >> GCAttrShift); }
312  void setObjCGCAttr(GC type) {
313  Mask = (Mask & ~GCAttrMask) | (type << GCAttrShift);
314  }
315  void removeObjCGCAttr() { setObjCGCAttr(GCNone); }
316  void addObjCGCAttr(GC type) {
317  assert(type);
318  setObjCGCAttr(type);
319  }
320  Qualifiers withoutObjCGCAttr() const {
321  Qualifiers qs = *this;
322  qs.removeObjCGCAttr();
323  return qs;
324  }
325  Qualifiers withoutObjCLifetime() const {
326  Qualifiers qs = *this;
327  qs.removeObjCLifetime();
328  return qs;
329  }
330  Qualifiers withoutAddressSpace() const {
331  Qualifiers qs = *this;
332  qs.removeAddressSpace();
333  return qs;
334  }
335 
336  bool hasObjCLifetime() const { return Mask & LifetimeMask; }
337  ObjCLifetime getObjCLifetime() const {
338  return ObjCLifetime((Mask & LifetimeMask) >> LifetimeShift);
339  }
340  void setObjCLifetime(ObjCLifetime type) {
341  Mask = (Mask & ~LifetimeMask) | (type << LifetimeShift);
342  }
343  void removeObjCLifetime() { setObjCLifetime(OCL_None); }
344  void addObjCLifetime(ObjCLifetime type) {
345  assert(type);
346  assert(!hasObjCLifetime());
347  Mask |= (type << LifetimeShift);
348  }
349 
350  /// True if the lifetime is neither None or ExplicitNone.
351  bool hasNonTrivialObjCLifetime() const {
352  ObjCLifetime lifetime = getObjCLifetime();
353  return (lifetime > OCL_ExplicitNone);
354  }
355 
356  /// True if the lifetime is either strong or weak.
357  bool hasStrongOrWeakObjCLifetime() const {
358  ObjCLifetime lifetime = getObjCLifetime();
359  return (lifetime == OCL_Strong || lifetime == OCL_Weak);
360  }
361 
362  bool hasAddressSpace() const { return Mask & AddressSpaceMask; }
363  LangAS getAddressSpace() const {
364  return static_cast<LangAS>(Mask >> AddressSpaceShift);
365  }
366  bool hasTargetSpecificAddressSpace() const {
367  return isTargetAddressSpace(getAddressSpace());
368  }
369  /// Get the address space attribute value to be printed by diagnostics.
370  unsigned getAddressSpaceAttributePrintValue() const {
371  auto Addr = getAddressSpace();
372  // This function is not supposed to be used with language specific
373  // address spaces. If that happens, the diagnostic message should consider
374  // printing the QualType instead of the address space value.
375  assert(Addr == LangAS::Default || hasTargetSpecificAddressSpace());
376  if (Addr != LangAS::Default)
377  return toTargetAddressSpace(Addr);
378  // TODO: The diagnostic messages where Addr may be 0 should be fixed
379  // since it cannot differentiate the situation where 0 denotes the default
380  // address space or user specified __attribute__((address_space(0))).
381  return 0;
382  }
383  void setAddressSpace(LangAS space) {
384  assert((unsigned)space <= MaxAddressSpace);
385  Mask = (Mask & ~AddressSpaceMask)
386  | (((uint32_t) space) << AddressSpaceShift);
387  }
388  void removeAddressSpace() { setAddressSpace(LangAS::Default); }
389  void addAddressSpace(LangAS space, bool AllowDefaultAddrSpace = false) {
390  assert(space != LangAS::Default || AllowDefaultAddrSpace);
391  setAddressSpace(space);
392  }
393 
394  // Fast qualifiers are those that can be allocated directly
395  // on a QualType object.
396  bool hasFastQualifiers() const { return getFastQualifiers(); }
397  unsigned getFastQualifiers() const { return Mask & FastMask; }
398  void setFastQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
399  assert(!(mask & ~FastMask) && "bitmask contains non-fast qualifier bits");
400  Mask = (Mask & ~FastMask) | mask;
401  }
402  void removeFastQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
403  assert(!(mask & ~FastMask) && "bitmask contains non-fast qualifier bits");
404  Mask &= ~mask;
405  }
406  void removeFastQualifiers() {
407  removeFastQualifiers(FastMask);
408  }
409  void addFastQualifiers(unsigned mask) {
410  assert(!(mask & ~FastMask) && "bitmask contains non-fast qualifier bits");
411  Mask |= mask;
412  }
413 
414  /// Return true if the set contains any qualifiers which require an ExtQuals
415  /// node to be allocated.
416  bool hasNonFastQualifiers() const { return Mask & ~FastMask; }
417  Qualifiers getNonFastQualifiers() const {
418  Qualifiers Quals = *this;
419  Quals.setFastQualifiers(0);
420  return Quals;
421  }
422 
423  /// Return true if the set contains any qualifiers.
424  bool hasQualifiers() const { return Mask; }
425  bool empty() const { return !Mask; }
426 
427  /// Add the qualifiers from the given set to this set.
428  void addQualifiers(Qualifiers Q) {
429  // If the other set doesn't have any non-boolean qualifiers, just
430  // bit-or it in.
431  if (!(Q.Mask & ~CVRMask))
432  Mask |= Q.Mask;
433  else {
434  Mask |= (Q.Mask & CVRMask);
435  if (Q.hasAddressSpace())
436  addAddressSpace(Q.getAddressSpace());
437  if (Q.hasObjCGCAttr())
438  addObjCGCAttr(Q.getObjCGCAttr());
439  if (Q.hasObjCLifetime())
440  addObjCLifetime(Q.getObjCLifetime());
441  }
442  }
443 
444  /// Remove the qualifiers from the given set from this set.
445  void removeQualifiers(Qualifiers Q) {
446  // If the other set doesn't have any non-boolean qualifiers, just
447  // bit-and the inverse in.
448  if (!(Q.Mask & ~CVRMask))
449  Mask &= ~Q.Mask;
450  else {
451  Mask &= ~(Q.Mask & CVRMask);
452  if (getObjCGCAttr() == Q.getObjCGCAttr())
453  removeObjCGCAttr();
454  if (getObjCLifetime() == Q.getObjCLifetime())
455  removeObjCLifetime();
456  if (getAddressSpace() == Q.getAddressSpace())
457  removeAddressSpace();
458  }
459  }
460 
461  /// Add the qualifiers from the given set to this set, given that
462  /// they don't conflict.
463  void addConsistentQualifiers(Qualifiers qs) {
464  assert(getAddressSpace() == qs.getAddressSpace() ||
465  !hasAddressSpace() || !qs.hasAddressSpace());
466  assert(getObjCGCAttr() == qs.getObjCGCAttr() ||
467  !hasObjCGCAttr() || !qs.hasObjCGCAttr());
468  assert(getObjCLifetime() == qs.getObjCLifetime() ||
469  !hasObjCLifetime() || !qs.hasObjCLifetime());
470  Mask |= qs.Mask;
471  }
472 
473  /// Returns true if address space A is equal to or a superset of B.
474  /// OpenCL v2.0 defines conversion rules (OpenCLC v2.0 s6.5.5) and notion of
475  /// overlapping address spaces.
476  /// CL1.1 or CL1.2:
477  /// every address space is a superset of itself.
478  /// CL2.0 adds:
479  /// __generic is a superset of any address space except for __constant.
480  static bool isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(LangAS A, LangAS B) {
481  // Address spaces must match exactly.
482  return A == B ||
483  // Otherwise in OpenCLC v2.0 s6.5.5: every address space except
484  // for __constant can be used as __generic.
485  (A == LangAS::opencl_generic && B != LangAS::opencl_constant) ||
486  // We also define global_device and global_host address spaces,
487  // to distinguish global pointers allocated on host from pointers
488  // allocated on device, which are a subset of __global.
489  (A == LangAS::opencl_global && (B == LangAS::opencl_global_device ||
490  B == LangAS::opencl_global_host)) ||
491  (A == LangAS::sycl_global && (B == LangAS::sycl_global_device ||
492  B == LangAS::sycl_global_host)) ||
493  // Consider pointer size address spaces to be equivalent to default.
494  ((isPtrSizeAddressSpace(A) || A == LangAS::Default) &&
495  (isPtrSizeAddressSpace(B) || B == LangAS::Default)) ||
496  // Default is a superset of SYCL address spaces.
497  (A == LangAS::Default &&
498  (B == LangAS::sycl_private || B == LangAS::sycl_local ||
499  B == LangAS::sycl_global || B == LangAS::sycl_global_device ||
500  B == LangAS::sycl_global_host)) ||
501  // In HIP device compilation, any cuda address space is allowed
502  // to implicitly cast into the default address space.
503  (A == LangAS::Default &&
504  (B == LangAS::cuda_constant || B == LangAS::cuda_device ||
505  B == LangAS::cuda_shared));
506  }
507 
508  /// Returns true if the address space in these qualifiers is equal to or
509  /// a superset of the address space in the argument qualifiers.
510  bool isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(Qualifiers other) const {
511  return isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(getAddressSpace(), other.getAddressSpace());
512  }
513 
514  /// Determines if these qualifiers compatibly include another set.
515  /// Generally this answers the question of whether an object with the other
516  /// qualifiers can be safely used as an object with these qualifiers.
517  bool compatiblyIncludes(Qualifiers other) const {
518  return isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(other) &&
519  // ObjC GC qualifiers can match, be added, or be removed, but can't
520  // be changed.
521  (getObjCGCAttr() == other.getObjCGCAttr() || !hasObjCGCAttr() ||
522  !other.hasObjCGCAttr()) &&
523  // ObjC lifetime qualifiers must match exactly.
524  getObjCLifetime() == other.getObjCLifetime() &&
525  // CVR qualifiers may subset.
526  (((Mask & CVRMask) | (other.Mask & CVRMask)) == (Mask & CVRMask)) &&
527  // U qualifier may superset.
528  (!other.hasUnaligned() || hasUnaligned());
529  }
530 
531  /// Determines if these qualifiers compatibly include another set of
532  /// qualifiers from the narrow perspective of Objective-C ARC lifetime.
533  ///
534  /// One set of Objective-C lifetime qualifiers compatibly includes the other
535  /// if the lifetime qualifiers match, or if both are non-__weak and the
536  /// including set also contains the 'const' qualifier, or both are non-__weak
537  /// and one is None (which can only happen in non-ARC modes).
538  bool compatiblyIncludesObjCLifetime(Qualifiers other) const {
539  if (getObjCLifetime() == other.getObjCLifetime())
540  return true;
541 
542  if (getObjCLifetime() == OCL_Weak || other.getObjCLifetime() == OCL_Weak)
543  return false;
544 
545  if (getObjCLifetime() == OCL_None || other.getObjCLifetime() == OCL_None)
546  return true;
547 
548  return hasConst();
549  }
550 
551  /// Determine whether this set of qualifiers is a strict superset of
552  /// another set of qualifiers, not considering qualifier compatibility.
553  bool isStrictSupersetOf(Qualifiers Other) const;
554 
555  bool operator==(Qualifiers Other) const { return Mask == Other.Mask; }
556  bool operator!=(Qualifiers Other) const { return Mask != Other.Mask; }
557 
558  explicit operator bool() const { return hasQualifiers(); }
559 
560  Qualifiers &operator+=(Qualifiers R) {
561  addQualifiers(R);
562  return *this;
563  }
564 
565  // Union two qualifier sets. If an enumerated qualifier appears
566  // in both sets, use the one from the right.
567  friend Qualifiers operator+(Qualifiers L, Qualifiers R) {
568  L += R;
569  return L;
570  }
571 
572  Qualifiers &operator-=(Qualifiers R) {
573  removeQualifiers(R);
574  return *this;
575  }
576 
577  /// Compute the difference between two qualifier sets.
578  friend Qualifiers operator-(Qualifiers L, Qualifiers R) {
579  L -= R;
580  return L;
581  }
582 
583  std::string getAsString() const;
584  std::string getAsString(const PrintingPolicy &Policy) const;
585 
586  static std::string getAddrSpaceAsString(LangAS AS);
587 
588  bool isEmptyWhenPrinted(const PrintingPolicy &Policy) const;
589  void print(raw_ostream &OS, const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
590  bool appendSpaceIfNonEmpty = false) const;
591 
592  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) const {
593  ID.AddInteger(Mask);
594  }
595 
596 private:
597  // bits: |0 1 2|3|4 .. 5|6 .. 8|9 ... 31|
598  // |C R V|U|GCAttr|Lifetime|AddressSpace|
599  uint32_t Mask = 0;
600 
601  static const uint32_t UMask = 0x8;
602  static const uint32_t UShift = 3;
603  static const uint32_t GCAttrMask = 0x30;
604  static const uint32_t GCAttrShift = 4;
605  static const uint32_t LifetimeMask = 0x1C0;
606  static const uint32_t LifetimeShift = 6;
607  static const uint32_t AddressSpaceMask =
608  ~(CVRMask | UMask | GCAttrMask | LifetimeMask);
609  static const uint32_t AddressSpaceShift = 9;
610 };
611 
612 /// A std::pair-like structure for storing a qualified type split
613 /// into its local qualifiers and its locally-unqualified type.
614 struct SplitQualType {
615  /// The locally-unqualified type.
616  const Type *Ty = nullptr;
617 
618  /// The local qualifiers.
619  Qualifiers Quals;
620 
621  SplitQualType() = default;
622  SplitQualType(const Type *ty, Qualifiers qs) : Ty(ty), Quals(qs) {}
623 
624  SplitQualType getSingleStepDesugaredType() const; // end of this file
625 
626  // Make std::tie work.
627  std::pair<const Type *,Qualifiers> asPair() const {
628  return std::pair<const Type *, Qualifiers>(Ty, Quals);
629  }
630 
631  friend bool operator==(SplitQualType a, SplitQualType b) {
632  return a.Ty == b.Ty && a.Quals == b.Quals;
633  }
634  friend bool operator!=(SplitQualType a, SplitQualType b) {
635  return a.Ty != b.Ty || a.Quals != b.Quals;
636  }
637 };
638 
639 /// The kind of type we are substituting Objective-C type arguments into.
640 ///
641 /// The kind of substitution affects the replacement of type parameters when
642 /// no concrete type information is provided, e.g., when dealing with an
643 /// unspecialized type.
644 enum class ObjCSubstitutionContext {
645  /// An ordinary type.
646  Ordinary,
647 
648  /// The result type of a method or function.
649  Result,
650 
651  /// The parameter type of a method or function.
652  Parameter,
653 
654  /// The type of a property.
655  Property,
656 
657  /// The superclass of a type.
658  Superclass,
659 };
660 
661 /// A (possibly-)qualified type.
662 ///
663 /// For efficiency, we don't store CV-qualified types as nodes on their
664 /// own: instead each reference to a type stores the qualifiers. This
665 /// greatly reduces the number of nodes we need to allocate for types (for
666 /// example we only need one for 'int', 'const int', 'volatile int',
667 /// 'const volatile int', etc).
668 ///
669 /// As an added efficiency bonus, instead of making this a pair, we
670 /// just store the two bits we care about in the low bits of the
671 /// pointer. To handle the packing/unpacking, we make QualType be a
672 /// simple wrapper class that acts like a smart pointer. A third bit
673 /// indicates whether there are extended qualifiers present, in which
674 /// case the pointer points to a special structure.
675 class QualType {
676  friend class QualifierCollector;
677 
678  // Thankfully, these are efficiently composable.
679  llvm::PointerIntPair<llvm::PointerUnion<const Type *, const ExtQuals *>,
680  Qualifiers::FastWidth> Value;
681 
682  const ExtQuals *getExtQualsUnsafe() const {
683  return Value.getPointer().get<const ExtQuals*>();
684  }
685 
686  const Type *getTypePtrUnsafe() const {
687  return Value.getPointer().get<const Type*>();
688  }
689 
690  const ExtQualsTypeCommonBase *getCommonPtr() const {
691  assert(!isNull() && "Cannot retrieve a NULL type pointer");
692  auto CommonPtrVal = reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(Value.getOpaqueValue());
693  CommonPtrVal &= ~(uintptr_t)((1 << TypeAlignmentInBits) - 1);
694  return reinterpret_cast<ExtQualsTypeCommonBase*>(CommonPtrVal);
695  }
696 
697 public:
698  QualType() = default;
699  QualType(const Type *Ptr, unsigned Quals) : Value(Ptr, Quals) {}
700  QualType(const ExtQuals *Ptr, unsigned Quals) : Value(Ptr, Quals) {}
701 
702  unsigned getLocalFastQualifiers() const { return Value.getInt(); }
703  void setLocalFastQualifiers(unsigned Quals) { Value.setInt(Quals); }
704 
705  /// Retrieves a pointer to the underlying (unqualified) type.
706  ///
707  /// This function requires that the type not be NULL. If the type might be
708  /// NULL, use the (slightly less efficient) \c getTypePtrOrNull().
709  const Type *getTypePtr() const;
710 
711  const Type *getTypePtrOrNull() const;
712 
713  /// Retrieves a pointer to the name of the base type.
714  const IdentifierInfo *getBaseTypeIdentifier() const;
715 
716  /// Divides a QualType into its unqualified type and a set of local
717  /// qualifiers.
718  SplitQualType split() const;
719 
720  void *getAsOpaquePtr() const { return Value.getOpaqueValue(); }
721 
722  static QualType getFromOpaquePtr(const void *Ptr) {
723  QualType T;
724  T.Value.setFromOpaqueValue(const_cast<void*>(Ptr));
725  return T;
726  }
727 
728  const Type &operator*() const {
729  return *getTypePtr();
730  }
731 
732  const Type *operator->() const {
733  return getTypePtr();
734  }
735 
736  bool isCanonical() const;
737  bool isCanonicalAsParam() const;
738 
739  /// Return true if this QualType doesn't point to a type yet.
740  bool isNull() const {
741  return Value.getPointer().isNull();
742  }
743 
744  /// Determine whether this particular QualType instance has the
745  /// "const" qualifier set, without looking through typedefs that may have
746  /// added "const" at a different level.
747  bool isLocalConstQualified() const {
748  return (getLocalFastQualifiers() & Qualifiers::Const);
749  }
750 
751  /// Determine whether this type is const-qualified.
752  bool isConstQualified() const;
753 
754  /// Determine whether this particular QualType instance has the
755  /// "restrict" qualifier set, without looking through typedefs that may have
756  /// added "restrict" at a different level.
757  bool isLocalRestrictQualified() const {
758  return (getLocalFastQualifiers() & Qualifiers::Restrict);
759  }
760 
761  /// Determine whether this type is restrict-qualified.
762  bool isRestrictQualified() const;
763 
764  /// Determine whether this particular QualType instance has the
765  /// "volatile" qualifier set, without looking through typedefs that may have
766  /// added "volatile" at a different level.
767  bool isLocalVolatileQualified() const {
768  return (getLocalFastQualifiers() & Qualifiers::Volatile);
769  }
770 
771  /// Determine whether this type is volatile-qualified.
772  bool isVolatileQualified() const;
773 
774  /// Determine whether this particular QualType instance has any
775  /// qualifiers, without looking through any typedefs that might add
776  /// qualifiers at a different level.
777  bool hasLocalQualifiers() const {
778  return getLocalFastQualifiers() || hasLocalNonFastQualifiers();
779  }
780 
781  /// Determine whether this type has any qualifiers.
782  bool hasQualifiers() const;
783 
784  /// Determine whether this particular QualType instance has any
785  /// "non-fast" qualifiers, e.g., those that are stored in an ExtQualType
786  /// instance.
787  bool hasLocalNonFastQualifiers() const {
788  return Value.getPointer().is<const ExtQuals*>();
789  }
790 
791  /// Retrieve the set of qualifiers local to this particular QualType
792  /// instance, not including any qualifiers acquired through typedefs or
793  /// other sugar.
794  Qualifiers getLocalQualifiers() const;
795 
796  /// Retrieve the set of qualifiers applied to this type.
797  Qualifiers getQualifiers() const;
798 
799  /// Retrieve the set of CVR (const-volatile-restrict) qualifiers
800  /// local to this particular QualType instance, not including any qualifiers
801  /// acquired through typedefs or other sugar.
802  unsigned getLocalCVRQualifiers() const {
803  return getLocalFastQualifiers();
804  }
805 
806  /// Retrieve the set of CVR (const-volatile-restrict) qualifiers
807  /// applied to this type.
808  unsigned getCVRQualifiers() const;
809 
810  bool isConstant(const ASTContext& Ctx) const {
811  return QualType::isConstant(*this, Ctx);
812  }

814  /// Determine whether this is a Plain Old Data (POD) type (C++ 3.9p10).
815  bool isPODType(const ASTContext &Context) const;

825  bool isCXX11PODType(const ASTContext &Context) const;

840  // Don't promise in the API that anything besides 'const' can be
841  // easily added.
842 
843  /// Add the `const` type qualifier to this QualType.
844  void addConst() {
845  addFastQualifiers(Qualifiers::Const);
846  }
847  QualType withConst() const {
848  return withFastQualifiers(Qualifiers::Const);

870 
871  void addFastQualifiers(unsigned TQs) {
872  assert(!(TQs & ~Qualifiers::FastMask)
873  && "non-fast qualifier bits set in mask!");
874  Value.setInt(Value.getInt() | TQs);
875  }
876 
877  void removeLocalConst();
878  void removeLocalVolatile();
879  void removeLocalRestrict();
880  void removeLocalCVRQualifiers(unsigned Mask);
881 
882  void removeLocalFastQualifiers() { Value.setInt(0); }
883  void removeLocalFastQualifiers(unsigned Mask) {
884  assert(!(Mask & ~Qualifiers::FastMask) && "mask has non-fast qualifiers");
885  Value.setInt(Value.getInt() & ~Mask);
886  }
887 
888  // Creates a type with the given qualifiers in addition to any
889  // qualifiers already on this type.
890  QualType withFastQualifiers(unsigned TQs) const {
891  QualType T = *this;
892  T.addFastQualifiers(TQs);
893  return T;
894  }
895 
896  // Creates a type with exactly the given fast qualifiers, removing
897  // any existing fast qualifiers.
898  QualType withExactLocalFastQualifiers(unsigned TQs) const {
899  return withoutLocalFastQualifiers().withFastQualifiers(TQs);
900  }
901 
902  // Removes fast qualifiers, but leaves any extended qualifiers in place.
903  QualType withoutLocalFastQualifiers() const {
904  QualType T = *this;
905  T.removeLocalFastQualifiers();
906  return T;
907  }

909  QualType getCanonicalType() const;
910 
911  /// Return this type with all of the instance-specific qualifiers
912  /// removed, but without removing any qualifiers that may have been applied
913  /// through typedefs.
914  QualType getLocalUnqualifiedType() const { return QualType(getTypePtr(), 0); }
915 
916  /// Retrieve the unqualified variant of the given type,
917  /// removing as little sugar as possible.
918  ///
919  /// This routine looks through various kinds of sugar to find the
920  /// least-desugared type that is unqualified. For example, given:
921  ///
922  /// \code
923  /// typedef int Integer;
924  /// typedef const Integer CInteger;
925  /// typedef CInteger DifferenceType;
926  /// \endcode
927  ///
928  /// Executing \c getUnqualifiedType() on the type \c DifferenceType will
929  /// desugar until we hit the type \c Integer, which has no qualifiers on it.
930  ///
931  /// The resulting type might still be qualified if it's sugar for an array
932  /// type. To strip qualifiers even from within a sugared array type, use
933  /// ASTContext::getUnqualifiedArrayType.
934  inline QualType getUnqualifiedType() const;
935 
936  /// Retrieve the unqualified variant of the given type, removing as little
937  /// sugar as possible.
938  ///
939  /// Like getUnqualifiedType(), but also returns the set of
940  /// qualifiers that were built up.
941  ///
942  /// The resulting type might still be qualified if it's sugar for an array
943  /// type. To strip qualifiers even from within a sugared array type, use
944  /// ASTContext::getUnqualifiedArrayType.
945  inline SplitQualType getSplitUnqualifiedType() const;
946 
947  /// Determine whether this type is more qualified than the other
948  /// given type, requiring exact equality for non-CVR qualifiers.
949  bool isMoreQualifiedThan(QualType Other) const;
950 
951  /// Determine whether this type is at least as qualified as the other
952  /// given type, requiring exact equality for non-CVR qualifiers.
953  bool isAtLeastAsQualifiedAs(QualType Other) const;
954 
955  QualType getNonReferenceType() const;
956 
957  /// Determine the type of a (typically non-lvalue) expression with the
958  /// specified result type.
959  ///
960  /// This routine should be used for expressions for which the return type is
961  /// explicitly specified (e.g., in a cast or call) and isn't necessarily
962  /// an lvalue. It removes a top-level reference (since there are no
963  /// expressions of reference type) and deletes top-level cvr-qualifiers
964  /// from non-class types (in C++) or all types (in C).
965  QualType getNonLValueExprType(const ASTContext &Context) const;
966 
967  /// Remove an outer pack expansion type (if any) from this type. Used as part
968  /// of converting the type of a declaration to the type of an expression that
969  /// references that expression. It's meaningless for an expression to have a
970  /// pack expansion type.
971  QualType getNonPackExpansionType() const;
972 
973  /// Return the specified type with any "sugar" removed from
974  /// the type. This takes off typedefs, typeof's etc. If the outer level of
975  /// the type is already concrete, it returns it unmodified. This is similar
976  /// to getting the canonical type, but it doesn't remove *all* typedefs. For
977  /// example, it returns "T*" as "T*", (not as "int*"), because the pointer is
978  /// concrete.
979  ///
980  /// Qualifiers are left in place.
981  QualType getDesugaredType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
982  return getDesugaredType(*this, Context);
983  }
984 
985  SplitQualType getSplitDesugaredType() const {
986  return getSplitDesugaredType(*this);
987  }
988 
989  /// Return the specified type with one level of "sugar" removed from
990  /// the type.
991  ///
992  /// This routine takes off the first typedef, typeof, etc. If the outer level
993  /// of the type is already concrete, it returns it unmodified.
994  QualType getSingleStepDesugaredType(const ASTContext &Context) const {
995  return getSingleStepDesugaredTypeImpl(*this, Context);
996  }
997 
998  /// Returns the specified type after dropping any
999  /// outer-level parentheses.
1000  QualType IgnoreParens() const {
1001  if (isa<ParenType>(*this))
1002  return QualType::IgnoreParens(*this);
1003  return *this;
1004  }

1006  /// Indicate whether the specified types and qualifiers are identical.
1007  friend bool operator==(const QualType &LHS, const QualType &RHS) {
1008  return LHS.Value == RHS.Value;
1009  }
1010  friend bool operator!=(const QualType &LHS, const QualType &RHS) {
1011  return LHS.Value != RHS.Value;
1012  }
1013  friend bool operator<(const QualType &LHS, const QualType &RHS) {
1014  return LHS.Value < RHS.Value;
1015  }

1087  /// Check if this type has any address space qualifier.
1088  inline bool hasAddressSpace() const;
1089 
1090  /// Return the address space of this type.
1091  inline LangAS getAddressSpace() const;
1092 
1093  /// Returns true if address space qualifiers overlap with T address space
1094  /// qualifiers.
1095  /// OpenCL C defines conversion rules for pointers to different address spaces
1096  /// and notion of overlapping address spaces.
1097  /// CL1.1 or CL1.2:
1098  /// address spaces overlap iff they are they same.
1099  /// OpenCL C v2.0 s6.5.5 adds:
1100  /// __generic overlaps with any address space except for __constant.
1101  bool isAddressSpaceOverlapping(QualType T) const {
1102  Qualifiers Q = getQualifiers();
1103  Qualifiers TQ = T.getQualifiers();
1104  // Address spaces overlap if at least one of them is a superset of another
1105  return Q.isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(TQ) || TQ.isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(Q);
1106  }

1113  return getObjCGCAttr() == Qualifiers::Weak;
1114  }

1116  /// true when Type is objc's strong.
1117  bool isObjCGCStrong() const {
1118  return getObjCGCAttr() == Qualifiers::Strong;

1137  enum PrimitiveDefaultInitializeKind {
1138  /// The type does not fall into any of the following categories. Note that
1139  /// this case is zero-valued so that values of this enum can be used as a
1140  /// boolean condition for non-triviality.
1141  PDIK_Trivial,
1142 
1143  /// The type is an Objective-C retainable pointer type that is qualified
1144  /// with the ARC __strong qualifier.
1145  PDIK_ARCStrong,
1146 
1147  /// The type is an Objective-C retainable pointer type that is qualified
1148  /// with the ARC __weak qualifier.
1149  PDIK_ARCWeak,
1150 
1151  /// The type is a struct containing a field whose type is not PCK_Trivial.
1152  PDIK_Struct
1153  };
1154 
1155  /// Functions to query basic properties of non-trivial C struct types.
1156 
1157  /// Check if this is a non-trivial type that would cause a C struct
1158  /// transitively containing this type to be non-trivial to default initialize
1159  /// and return the kind.
1160  PrimitiveDefaultInitializeKind
1161  isNonTrivialToPrimitiveDefaultInitialize() const;

1163  enum PrimitiveCopyKind {
1164  /// The type does not fall into any of the following categories. Note that
1165  /// this case is zero-valued so that values of this enum can be used as a
1166  /// boolean condition for non-triviality.
1167  PCK_Trivial,
1168 
1169  /// The type would be trivial except that it is volatile-qualified. Types
1170  /// that fall into one of the other non-trivial cases may additionally be
1171  /// volatile-qualified.
1172  PCK_VolatileTrivial,
1173 
1174  /// The type is an Objective-C retainable pointer type that is qualified
1175  /// with the ARC __strong qualifier.
1176  PCK_ARCStrong,
1177 
1178  /// The type is an Objective-C retainable pointer type that is qualified
1179  /// with the ARC __weak qualifier.
1180  PCK_ARCWeak,
1181 
1182  /// The type is a struct containing a field whose type is neither
1183  /// PCK_Trivial nor PCK_VolatileTrivial.
1184  /// Note that a C++ struct type does not necessarily match this; C++ copying
1185  /// semantics are too complex to express here, in part because they depend
1186  /// on the exact constructor or assignment operator that is chosen by
1187  /// overload resolution to do the copy.
1188  PCK_Struct
1189  };
1190 
1191  /// Check if this is a non-trivial type that would cause a C struct
1192  /// transitively containing this type to be non-trivial to copy and return the
1193  /// kind.
1194  PrimitiveCopyKind isNonTrivialToPrimitiveCopy() const;
1195 
1196  /// Check if this is a non-trivial type that would cause a C struct
1197  /// transitively containing this type to be non-trivial to destructively
1198  /// move and return the kind. Destructive move in this context is a C++-style
1199  /// move in which the source object is placed in a valid but unspecified state
1200  /// after it is moved, as opposed to a truly destructive move in which the
1201  /// source object is placed in an uninitialized state.
1202  PrimitiveCopyKind isNonTrivialToPrimitiveDestructiveMove() const;
1203 
1204  enum DestructionKind {
1205  DK_none,
1206  DK_cxx_destructor,
1207  DK_objc_strong_lifetime,
1208  DK_objc_weak_lifetime,
1209  DK_nontrivial_c_struct

1212  /// Returns a nonzero value if objects of this type require
1213  /// non-trivial work to clean up after. Non-zero because it's
1214  /// conceivable that qualifiers (objc_gc(weak)?) could make
1215  /// something require destruction.
1216  DestructionKind isDestructedType() const {
1217  return isDestructedTypeImpl(*this);

1222  /// to default-initialize. If this returns true,

1224  bool hasNonTrivialToPrimitiveDefaultInitializeCUnion() const;

1233  /// true, isNonTrivialToPrimitiveCopy returns PCK_Struct.
1234  bool hasNonTrivialToPrimitiveCopyCUnion() const;

1236  /// Determine whether expressions of the given type are forbidden
1237  /// from being lvalues in C.
1238  ///
1239  /// The expression types that are forbidden to be lvalues are:
1240  /// - 'void', but not qualified void
1241  /// - function types
1242  ///
1243  /// The exact rule here is C99 6.3.2.1:
1244  /// An lvalue is an expression with an object type or an incomplete
1245  /// type other than void.
1246  bool isCForbiddenLValueType() const;
1247 
1248  /// Substitute type arguments for the Objective-C type parameters used in the
1249  /// subject type.
1250  ///
1251  /// \param ctx ASTContext in which the type exists.
1252  ///
1253  /// \param typeArgs The type arguments that will be substituted for the
1254  /// Objective-C type parameters in the subject type, which are generally
1255  /// computed via \c Type::getObjCSubstitutions. If empty, the type
1256  /// parameters will be replaced with their bounds or id/Class, as appropriate
1257  /// for the context.
1258  ///
1259  /// \param context The context in which the subject type was written.
1260  ///
1261  /// \returns the resulting type.
1262  QualType substObjCTypeArgs(ASTContext &ctx,
1263  ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs,
1264  ObjCSubstitutionContext context) const;
1265 
1266  /// Substitute type arguments from an object type for the Objective-C type
1267  /// parameters used in the subject type.
1268  ///
1269  /// This operation combines the computation of type arguments for
1270  /// substitution (\c Type::getObjCSubstitutions) with the actual process of
1271  /// substitution (\c QualType::substObjCTypeArgs) for the convenience of
1272  /// callers that need to perform a single substitution in isolation.
1273  ///
1274  /// \param objectType The type of the object whose member type we're
1275  /// substituting into. For example, this might be the receiver of a message
1276  /// or the base of a property access.
1277  ///
1278  /// \param dc The declaration context from which the subject type was
1279  /// retrieved, which indicates (for example) which type parameters should
1280  /// be substituted.
1281  ///
1282  /// \param context The context in which the subject type was written.
1283  ///
1284  /// \returns the subject type after replacing all of the Objective-C type
1285  /// parameters with their corresponding arguments.
1286  QualType substObjCMemberType(QualType objectType,
1287  const DeclContext *dc,
1288  ObjCSubstitutionContext context) const;
1289 
1290  /// Strip Objective-C "__kindof" types from the given type.
1291  QualType stripObjCKindOfType(const ASTContext &ctx) const;
1292 
1293  /// Remove all qualifiers including _Atomic.
1294  QualType getAtomicUnqualifiedType() const;
1295 
1296 private:
1297  // These methods are implemented in a separate translation unit;
1298  // "static"-ize them to avoid creating temporary QualTypes in the
1299  // caller.
1300  static bool isConstant(QualType T, const ASTContext& Ctx);
1301  static QualType getDesugaredType(QualType T, const ASTContext &Context);
1302  static SplitQualType getSplitDesugaredType(QualType T);
1303  static SplitQualType getSplitUnqualifiedTypeImpl(QualType type);
1304  static QualType getSingleStepDesugaredTypeImpl(QualType type,
1305  const ASTContext &C);
1306  static QualType IgnoreParens(QualType T);
1307  static DestructionKind isDestructedTypeImpl(QualType type);
1308 
1309  /// Check if \param RD is or contains a non-trivial C union.
1310  static bool hasNonTrivialToPrimitiveDefaultInitializeCUnion(const RecordDecl *RD);
1311  static bool hasNonTrivialToPrimitiveDestructCUnion(const RecordDecl *RD);
1312  static bool hasNonTrivialToPrimitiveCopyCUnion(const RecordDecl *RD);
1313 };

1325  return Val.getTypePtr();

1348 /// Base class that is common to both the \c ExtQuals and \c Type
1349 /// classes, which allows \c QualType to access the common fields between the
1350 /// two.
1351 class ExtQualsTypeCommonBase {
1352  friend class ExtQuals;
1353  friend class QualType;
1354  friend class Type;
1355 
1356  /// The "base" type of an extended qualifiers type (\c ExtQuals) or
1357  /// a self-referential pointer (for \c Type).
1358  ///
1359  /// This pointer allows an efficient mapping from a QualType to its
1360  /// underlying type pointer.
1361  const Type *const BaseType;
1362 
1363  /// The canonical type of this type. A QualType.
1364  QualType CanonicalType;
1365 
1366  ExtQualsTypeCommonBase(const Type *baseType, QualType canon)
1367  : BaseType(baseType), CanonicalType(canon) {}
1368 };
1369 
1370 /// We can encode up to four bits in the low bits of a
1371 /// type pointer, but there are many more type qualifiers that we want
1372 /// to be able to apply to an arbitrary type. Therefore we have this
1373 /// struct, intended to be heap-allocated and used by QualType to
1374 /// store qualifiers.
1375 ///
1376 /// The current design tags the 'const', 'restrict', and 'volatile' qualifiers
1377 /// in three low bits on the QualType pointer; a fourth bit records whether
1378 /// the pointer is an ExtQuals node. The extended qualifiers (address spaces,
1379 /// Objective-C GC attributes) are much more rare.
1380 class ExtQuals : public ExtQualsTypeCommonBase, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
1381  // NOTE: changing the fast qualifiers should be straightforward as
1382  // long as you don't make 'const' non-fast.
1383  // 1. Qualifiers:
1384  // a) Modify the bitmasks (Qualifiers::TQ and DeclSpec::TQ).
1385  // Fast qualifiers must occupy the low-order bits.
1386  // b) Update Qualifiers::FastWidth and FastMask.
1387  // 2. QualType:
1388  // a) Update is{Volatile,Restrict}Qualified(), defined inline.
1389  // b) Update remove{Volatile,Restrict}, defined near the end of
1390  // this header.
1391  // 3. ASTContext:
1392  // a) Update get{Volatile,Restrict}Type.
1393 
1394  /// The immutable set of qualifiers applied by this node. Always contains
1395  /// extended qualifiers.
1396  Qualifiers Quals;
1397 
1398  ExtQuals *this_() { return this; }
1399 
1400 public:
1401  ExtQuals(const Type *baseType, QualType canon, Qualifiers quals)
1402  : ExtQualsTypeCommonBase(baseType,
1403  canon.isNull() ? QualType(this_(), 0) : canon),
1404  Quals(quals) {
1405  assert(Quals.hasNonFastQualifiers()
1406  && "ExtQuals created with no fast qualifiers");
1407  assert(!Quals.hasFastQualifiers()
1408  && "ExtQuals created with fast qualifiers");
1409  }
1410 
1411  Qualifiers getQualifiers() const { return Quals; }
1412 
1413  bool hasObjCGCAttr() const { return Quals.hasObjCGCAttr(); }
1414  Qualifiers::GC getObjCGCAttr() const { return Quals.getObjCGCAttr(); }
1415 
1416  bool hasObjCLifetime() const { return Quals.hasObjCLifetime(); }
1417  Qualifiers::ObjCLifetime getObjCLifetime() const {
1418  return Quals.getObjCLifetime();
1419  }
1420 
1421  bool hasAddressSpace() const { return Quals.hasAddressSpace(); }
1422  LangAS getAddressSpace() const { return Quals.getAddressSpace(); }
1423 
1424  const Type *getBaseType() const { return BaseType; }
1425 
1426 public:
1427  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) const {
1428  Profile(ID, getBaseType(), Quals);
1429  }
1430 
1431  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
1432  const Type *BaseType,
1433  Qualifiers Quals) {
1434  assert(!Quals.hasFastQualifiers() && "fast qualifiers in ExtQuals hash!");
1435  ID.AddPointer(BaseType);
1436  Quals.Profile(ID);
1437  }
1438 };
1439 
1440 /// The kind of C++11 ref-qualifier associated with a function type.
1441 /// This determines whether a member function's "this" object can be an
1442 /// lvalue, rvalue, or neither.
1443 enum RefQualifierKind {
1444  /// No ref-qualifier was provided.
1445  RQ_None = 0,
1446 
1447  /// An lvalue ref-qualifier was provided (\c &).
1448  RQ_LValue,
1449 
1450  /// An rvalue ref-qualifier was provided (\c &&).
1451  RQ_RValue
1452 };
1453 
1454 /// Which keyword(s) were used to create an AutoType.
1455 enum class AutoTypeKeyword {
1456  /// auto
1457  Auto,
1458 
1459  /// decltype(auto)
1460  DecltypeAuto,
1461 
1462  /// __auto_type (GNU extension)
1463  GNUAutoType
1464 };
1465 
1466 /// The base class of the type hierarchy.
1467 ///
1468 /// A central concept with types is that each type always has a canonical
1469 /// type. A canonical type is the type with any typedef names stripped out
1470 /// of it or the types it references. For example, consider:
1471 ///
1472 /// typedef int foo;
1473 /// typedef foo* bar;
1474 /// 'int *' 'foo *' 'bar'
1475 ///
1476 /// There will be a Type object created for 'int'. Since int is canonical, its
1477 /// CanonicalType pointer points to itself. There is also a Type for 'foo' (a
1478 /// TypedefType). Its CanonicalType pointer points to the 'int' Type. Next
1479 /// there is a PointerType that represents 'int*', which, like 'int', is
1480 /// canonical. Finally, there is a PointerType type for 'foo*' whose canonical
1481 /// type is 'int*', and there is a TypedefType for 'bar', whose canonical type
1482 /// is also 'int*'.
1483 ///
1484 /// Non-canonical types are useful for emitting diagnostics, without losing
1485 /// information about typedefs being used. Canonical types are useful for type
1486 /// comparisons (they allow by-pointer equality tests) and useful for reasoning
1487 /// about whether something has a particular form (e.g. is a function type),
1488 /// because they implicitly, recursively, strip all typedefs out of a type.
1489 ///
1490 /// Types, once created, are immutable.
1491 ///
1492 class alignas(8) Type : public ExtQualsTypeCommonBase {
1493 public:
1494  enum TypeClass {
1495 #define TYPE(Class, Base) Class,
1496 #define LAST_TYPE(Class) TypeLast = Class
1497 #define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Base)
1498 #include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.inc"
1499  };
1500 
1501 private:
1502  /// Bitfields required by the Type class.
1503  class TypeBitfields {
1504  friend class Type;
1505  template <class T> friend class TypePropertyCache;
1506 
1507  /// TypeClass bitfield - Enum that specifies what subclass this belongs to.
1508  unsigned TC : 8;
1509 
1510  /// Store information on the type dependency.
1511  unsigned Dependence : llvm::BitWidth<TypeDependence>;
1512 
1513  /// True if the cache (i.e. the bitfields here starting with
1514  /// 'Cache') is valid.
1515  mutable unsigned CacheValid : 1;
1516 
1517  /// Linkage of this type.
1518  mutable unsigned CachedLinkage : 3;
1519 
1520  /// Whether this type involves and local or unnamed types.
1521  mutable unsigned CachedLocalOrUnnamed : 1;
1522 
1523  /// Whether this type comes from an AST file.
1524  mutable unsigned FromAST : 1;
1525 
1526  bool isCacheValid() const {
1527  return CacheValid;
1528  }
1529 
1530  Linkage getLinkage() const {
1531  assert(isCacheValid() && "getting linkage from invalid cache");
1532  return static_cast<Linkage>(CachedLinkage);
1533  }
1534 
1535  bool hasLocalOrUnnamedType() const {
1536  assert(isCacheValid() && "getting linkage from invalid cache");
1537  return CachedLocalOrUnnamed;
1538  }
1539  };
1540  enum { NumTypeBits = 8 + llvm::BitWidth<TypeDependence> + 6 };
1541 
1542 protected:
1543  // These classes allow subclasses to somewhat cleanly pack bitfields
1544  // into Type.
1545 
1546  class ArrayTypeBitfields {
1547  friend class ArrayType;
1548 
1549  unsigned : NumTypeBits;
1550 
1551  /// CVR qualifiers from declarations like
1552  /// 'int X[static restrict 4]'. For function parameters only.
1553  unsigned IndexTypeQuals : 3;
1554 
1555  /// Storage class qualifiers from declarations like
1556  /// 'int X[static restrict 4]'. For function parameters only.
1557  /// Actually an ArrayType::ArraySizeModifier.
1558  unsigned SizeModifier : 3;
1559  };

1563 
1564  unsigned : NumTypeBits + 3 + 3;
1565 
1566  /// Whether we have a stored size expression.
1567  unsigned HasStoredSizeExpr : 1;
1568  };

1571  friend class BuiltinType;

1574 
1575  /// The kind (BuiltinType::Kind) of builtin type this is.
1576  unsigned Kind : 8;
1577  };

1579  /// FunctionTypeBitfields store various bits belonging to FunctionProtoType.
1580  /// Only common bits are stored here. Additional uncommon bits are stored
1581  /// in a trailing object after FunctionProtoType.
1582  class FunctionTypeBitfields {
1583  friend class FunctionProtoType;
1584  friend class FunctionType;
1585 
1586  unsigned : NumTypeBits;
1587 
1588  /// Extra information which affects how the function is called, like
1589  /// regparm and the calling convention.
1590  unsigned ExtInfo : 13;
1591 
1592  /// The ref-qualifier associated with a \c FunctionProtoType.
1593  ///
1594  /// This is a value of type \c RefQualifierKind.
1595  unsigned RefQualifier : 2;
1596 
1597  /// Used only by FunctionProtoType, put here to pack with the
1598  /// other bitfields.
1599  /// The qualifiers are part of FunctionProtoType because...
1600  ///
1601  /// C++ 8.3.5p4: The return type, the parameter type list and the
1602  /// cv-qualifier-seq, [...], are part of the function type.
1603  unsigned FastTypeQuals : Qualifiers::FastWidth;
1604  /// Whether this function has extended Qualifiers.
1605  unsigned HasExtQuals : 1;
1606 
1607  /// The number of parameters this function has, not counting '...'.
1608  /// According to [implimits] 8 bits should be enough here but this is
1609  /// somewhat easy to exceed with metaprogramming and so we would like to
1610  /// keep NumParams as wide as reasonably possible.
1611  unsigned NumParams : 16;
1612 
1613  /// The type of exception specification this function has.
1614  unsigned ExceptionSpecType : 4;
1615 
1616  /// Whether this function has extended parameter information.
1617  unsigned HasExtParameterInfos : 1;
1618 
1619  /// Whether the function is variadic.
1620  unsigned Variadic : 1;
1621 
1622  /// Whether this function has a trailing return type.
1623  unsigned HasTrailingReturn : 1;
1624  };
1625 
1626  class ObjCObjectTypeBitfields {
1627  friend class ObjCObjectType;
1628 
1629  unsigned : NumTypeBits;
1630 
1631  /// The number of type arguments stored directly on this object type.
1632  unsigned NumTypeArgs : 7;
1633 
1634  /// The number of protocols stored directly on this object type.
1635  unsigned NumProtocols : 6;
1636 
1637  /// Whether this is a "kindof" type.
1638  unsigned IsKindOf : 1;
1639  };

1641  class ReferenceTypeBitfields {
1642  friend class ReferenceType;
1643 
1644  unsigned : NumTypeBits;
1645 
1646  /// True if the type was originally spelled with an lvalue sigil.
1647  /// This is never true of rvalue references but can also be false
1648  /// on lvalue references because of C++0x [dcl.typedef]p9,
1649  /// as follows:
1650  ///
1651  /// typedef int &ref; // lvalue, spelled lvalue
1652  /// typedef int &&rvref; // rvalue
1653  /// ref &a; // lvalue, inner ref, spelled lvalue
1654  /// ref &&a; // lvalue, inner ref
1655  /// rvref &a; // lvalue, inner ref, spelled lvalue
1656  /// rvref &&a; // rvalue, inner ref
1657  unsigned SpelledAsLValue : 1;
1658 
1659  /// True if the inner type is a reference type. This only happens
1660  /// in non-canonical forms.
1661  unsigned InnerRef : 1;
1662  };

1814 private:
1815  template <class T> friend class TypePropertyCache;
1816 
1817  /// Set whether this type comes from an AST file.
1818  void setFromAST(bool V = true) const {
1819  TypeBits.FromAST = V;
1820  }
1821 
1822 protected:
1823  friend class ASTContext;
1824 
1825  Type(TypeClass tc, QualType canon, TypeDependence Dependence)
1826  : ExtQualsTypeCommonBase(this,
1827  canon.isNull() ? QualType(this_(), 0) : canon) {
1828  static_assert(sizeof(*this) <= 8 + sizeof(ExtQualsTypeCommonBase),
1829  "changing bitfields changed sizeof(Type)!");
1830  static_assert(alignof(decltype(*this)) % sizeof(void *) == 0,
1831  "Insufficient alignment!");
1832  TypeBits.TC = tc;
1833  TypeBits.Dependence = static_cast<unsigned>(Dependence);
1834  TypeBits.CacheValid = false;
1835  TypeBits.CachedLocalOrUnnamed = false;
1836  TypeBits.CachedLinkage = NoLinkage;
1837  TypeBits.FromAST = false;
1838  }
1839 
1840  // silence VC++ warning C4355: 'this' : used in base member initializer list
1841  Type *this_() { return this; }
1842 
1843  void setDependence(TypeDependence D) {
1844  TypeBits.Dependence = static_cast<unsigned>(D);
1845  }
1846 
1847  void addDependence(TypeDependence D) { setDependence(getDependence() | D); }
1848 
1849 public:
1850  friend class ASTReader;
1851  friend class ASTWriter;
1852  template <class T> friend class serialization::AbstractTypeReader;
1853  template <class T> friend class serialization::AbstractTypeWriter;
1854 
1855  Type(const Type &) = delete;
1856  Type(Type &&) = delete;
1857  Type &operator=(const Type &) = delete;
1858  Type &operator=(Type &&) = delete;
1859 
1860  TypeClass getTypeClass() const { return static_cast<TypeClass>(TypeBits.TC); }
1861 
1862  /// Whether this type comes from an AST file.
1863  bool isFromAST() const { return TypeBits.FromAST; }
1864 
1865  /// Whether this type is or contains an unexpanded parameter
1866  /// pack, used to support C++0x variadic templates.
1867  ///
1868  /// A type that contains a parameter pack shall be expanded by the
1869  /// ellipsis operator at some point. For example, the typedef in the
1870  /// following example contains an unexpanded parameter pack 'T':
1871  ///
1872  /// \code
1873  /// template<typename ...T>
1874  /// struct X {
1875  /// typedef T* pointer_types; // ill-formed; T is a parameter pack.
1876  /// };
1877  /// \endcode
1878  ///
1879  /// Note that this routine does not specify which
1880  bool containsUnexpandedParameterPack() const {
1881  return getDependence() & TypeDependence::UnexpandedPack;
1882  }
1883 
1884  /// Determines if this type would be canonical if it had no further
1885  /// qualification.
1886  bool isCanonicalUnqualified() const {
1887  return CanonicalType == QualType(this, 0);
1888  }
1889 
1890  /// Pull a single level of sugar off of this locally-unqualified type.
1891  /// Users should generally prefer SplitQualType::getSingleStepDesugaredType()
1892  /// or QualType::getSingleStepDesugaredType(const ASTContext&).
1893  QualType getLocallyUnqualifiedSingleStepDesugaredType() const;
1894 
1895  /// As an extension, we classify types as one of "sized" or "sizeless";
1896  /// every type is one or the other. Standard types are all sized;
1897  /// sizeless types are purely an extension.
1898  ///
1899  /// Sizeless types contain data with no specified size, alignment,
1900  /// or layout.
1901  bool isSizelessType() const;
1902  bool isSizelessBuiltinType() const;
1903 
1904  /// Determines if this is a sizeless type supported by the
1905  /// 'arm_sve_vector_bits' type attribute, which can be applied to a single
1906  /// SVE vector or predicate, excluding tuple types such as svint32x4_t.
1907  bool isVLSTBuiltinType() const;
1908 
1909  /// Returns the representative type for the element of an SVE builtin type.
1910  /// This is used to represent fixed-length SVE vectors created with the
1911  /// 'arm_sve_vector_bits' type attribute as VectorType.
1912  QualType getSveEltType(const ASTContext &Ctx) const;
1913 
1914  /// Types are partitioned into 3 broad categories (C99 6.2.5p1):
1915  /// object types, function types, and incomplete types.
1916 
1917  /// Return true if this is an incomplete type.
1918  /// A type that can describe objects, but which lacks information needed to
1919  /// determine its size (e.g. void, or a fwd declared struct). Clients of this
1920  /// routine will need to determine if the size is actually required.
1921  ///
1922  /// Def If non-null, and the type refers to some kind of declaration
1923  /// that can be completed (such as a C struct, C++ class, or Objective-C
1924  /// class), will be set to the declaration.
1925  bool isIncompleteType(NamedDecl **Def = nullptr) const;
1926 
1927  /// Return true if this is an incomplete or object
1928  /// type, in other words, not a function type.
1929  bool isIncompleteOrObjectType() const {
1930  return !isFunctionType();
1931  }
1932 
1933  /// Determine whether this type is an object type.
1934  bool isObjectType() const {
1935  // C++ [basic.types]p8:
1936  // An object type is a (possibly cv-qualified) type that is not a
1937  // function type, not a reference type, and not a void type.
1938  return !isReferenceType() && !isFunctionType() && !isVoidType();
1939  }

2465 
2466  QualType getCanonicalTypeInternal() const {
2467  return CanonicalType;
2468  }
2469 
2470  CanQualType getCanonicalTypeUnqualified() const; // in CanonicalType.h
2471  void dump() const;
2472  void dump(llvm::raw_ostream &OS, const ASTContext &Context) const;
2473 };

2475 /// This will check for a TypedefType by removing any existing sugar
2476 /// until it reaches a TypedefType or a non-sugared type.
2477 template <> const TypedefType *Type::getAs() const;
2478 
2479 /// This will check for a TemplateSpecializationType by removing any
2480 /// existing sugar until it reaches a TemplateSpecializationType or a
2481 /// non-sugared type.
2482 template <> const TemplateSpecializationType *Type::getAs() const;
2483 
2484 /// This will check for an AttributedType by removing any existing sugar
2485 /// until it reaches an AttributedType or a non-sugared type.
2486 template <> const AttributedType *Type::getAs() const;
2487 
2488 // We can do canonical leaf types faster, because we don't have to
2489 // worry about preserving child type decoration.
2490 #define TYPE(Class, Base)
2491 #define LEAF_TYPE(Class) \
2492 template <> inline const Class##Type *Type::getAs() const { \
2493  return dyn_cast<Class##Type>(CanonicalType); \
2494 } \
2495 template <> inline const Class##Type *Type::castAs() const { \
2496  return cast<Class##Type>(CanonicalType); \
2497 }
2498 #include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.inc"
2499 
2500 /// This class is used for builtin types like 'int'. Builtin
2501 /// types are always canonical and have a literal name field.
2502 class BuiltinType : public Type {
2503 public:
2504  enum Kind {
2505 // OpenCL image types
2506 #define IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id, SingletonId, Access, Suffix) Id,
2507 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
2508 #define IMAGE_TYPE(ImgType, Id, SingletonId, Access, Suffix) Sampled##Id,
2509 #define IMAGE_WRITE_TYPE(Type, Id, Ext)
2510 #define IMAGE_READ_WRITE_TYPE(Type, Id, Ext)
2511 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLImageTypes.def"
2512 // OpenCL extension types
2513 #define EXT_OPAQUE_TYPE(ExtType, Id, Ext) Id,
2514 #include "clang/Basic/OpenCLExtensionTypes.def"
2515 // SVE Types
2516 #define SVE_TYPE(Name, Id, SingletonId) Id,
2517 #include "clang/Basic/AArch64SVEACLETypes.def"
2518 // PPC MMA Types
2519 #define PPC_VECTOR_TYPE(Name, Id, Size) Id,
2520 #include "clang/Basic/PPCTypes.def"
2521 // RVV Types
2522 #define RVV_TYPE(Name, Id, SingletonId) Id,
2523 #include "clang/Basic/RISCVVTypes.def"
2524 // All other builtin types
2525 #define BUILTIN_TYPE(Id, SingletonId) Id,
2526 #define LAST_BUILTIN_TYPE(Id) LastKind = Id
2527 #include "clang/AST/BuiltinTypes.def"
2528  };
2529 
2530 private:
2531  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
2532 
2533  BuiltinType(Kind K)
2534  : Type(Builtin, QualType(),
2535  K == Dependent ? TypeDependence::DependentInstantiation
2536  : TypeDependence::None) {
2537  BuiltinTypeBits.Kind = K;
2538  }
2539 
2540 public:
2541  Kind getKind() const { return static_cast<Kind>(BuiltinTypeBits.Kind); }
2542  StringRef getName(const PrintingPolicy &Policy) const;
2543 
2544  const char *getNameAsCString(const PrintingPolicy &Policy) const {
2545  // The StringRef is null-terminated.
2546  StringRef str = getName(Policy);
2547  assert(!str.empty() && str.data()[str.size()] == '\0');
2548  return str.data();
2549  }
2550 
2551  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
2552  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
2553 
2554  bool isInteger() const {
2555  return getKind() >= Bool && getKind() <= Int128;
2556  }
2557 
2558  bool isSignedInteger() const {
2559  return getKind() >= Char_S && getKind() <= Int128;
2560  }
2561 
2562  bool isUnsignedInteger() const {
2563  return getKind() >= Bool && getKind() <= UInt128;
2564  }
2565 
2566  bool isFloatingPoint() const {
2567  return getKind() >= Half && getKind() <= Ibm128;
2568  }
2569 
2570  bool isSVEBool() const { return getKind() == Kind::SveBool; }
2571 
2572  /// Determines whether the given kind corresponds to a placeholder type.
2573  static bool isPlaceholderTypeKind(Kind K) {
2574  return K >= Overload;
2575  }
2576 
2577  /// Determines whether this type is a placeholder type, i.e. a type
2578  /// which cannot appear in arbitrary positions in a fully-formed
2579  /// expression.
2580  bool isPlaceholderType() const {
2581  return isPlaceholderTypeKind(getKind());
2582  }
2583 
2584  /// Determines whether this type is a placeholder type other than
2585  /// Overload. Most placeholder types require only syntactic
2586  /// information about their context in order to be resolved (e.g.
2587  /// whether it is a call expression), which means they can (and
2588  /// should) be resolved in an earlier "phase" of analysis.
2589  /// Overload expressions sometimes pick up further information
2590  /// from their context, like whether the context expects a
2591  /// specific function-pointer type, and so frequently need
2592  /// special treatment.
2593  bool isNonOverloadPlaceholderType() const {
2594  return getKind() > Overload;
2595  }
2596 
2597  static bool classof(const Type *T) { return T->getTypeClass() == Builtin; }
2598 };

2681 /// Represents a type which was implicitly adjusted by the semantic
2682 /// engine for arbitrary reasons. For example, array and function types can
2683 /// decay, and function types can have their calling conventions adjusted.
2684 class AdjustedType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {

2687 
2688 protected:
2689  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
2690

2692  QualType CanonicalPtr)

2694  OriginalTy(OriginalTy), AdjustedTy(AdjustedTy) {}
2695 
2696 public:
2697  QualType getOriginalType() const { return OriginalTy; }
2698  QualType getAdjustedType() const { return AdjustedTy; }

2705  }
2706

2708  ID.AddPointer(Orig.getAsOpaquePtr());
2709  ID.AddPointer(New.getAsOpaquePtr());
2710  }

2714  }

2765 /// Base for LValueReferenceType and RValueReferenceType
2766 class ReferenceType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
2767  QualType PointeeType;
2768 
2769 protected:
2770  ReferenceType(TypeClass tc, QualType Referencee, QualType CanonicalRef,
2771  bool SpelledAsLValue)
2772  : Type(tc, CanonicalRef, Referencee->getDependence()),
2773  PointeeType(Referencee) {
2774  ReferenceTypeBits.SpelledAsLValue = SpelledAsLValue;
2775  ReferenceTypeBits.InnerRef = Referencee->isReferenceType();
2776  }
2777 
2778 public:
2779  bool isSpelledAsLValue() const { return ReferenceTypeBits.SpelledAsLValue; }
2780  bool isInnerRef() const { return ReferenceTypeBits.InnerRef; }
2781 
2782  QualType getPointeeTypeAsWritten() const { return PointeeType; }
2783 
2784  QualType getPointeeType() const {
2785  // FIXME: this might strip inner qualifiers; okay?
2786  const ReferenceType *T = this;
2787  while (T->isInnerRef())
2788  T = T->PointeeType->castAs<ReferenceType>();
2789  return T->PointeeType;
2790  }
2791 
2792  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
2793  Profile(ID, PointeeType, isSpelledAsLValue());
2794  }
2795 
2796  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
2797  QualType Referencee,
2798  bool SpelledAsLValue) {
2799  ID.AddPointer(Referencee.getAsOpaquePtr());
2800  ID.AddBoolean(SpelledAsLValue);
2801  }
2802 
2803  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
2804  return T->getTypeClass() == LValueReference ||
2805  T->getTypeClass() == RValueReference;
2806  }
2807 };

2843 /// A pointer to member type per C++ 8.3.3 - Pointers to members.
2844 ///
2845 /// This includes both pointers to data members and pointer to member functions.
2846 class MemberPointerType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
2847  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
2848 
2849  QualType PointeeType;
2850 
2851  /// The class of which the pointee is a member. Must ultimately be a
2852  /// RecordType, but could be a typedef or a template parameter too.
2853  const Type *Class;
2854 
2855  MemberPointerType(QualType Pointee, const Type *Cls, QualType CanonicalPtr)
2856  : Type(MemberPointer, CanonicalPtr,
2857  (Cls->getDependence() & ~TypeDependence::VariablyModified) |
2858  Pointee->getDependence()),
2859  PointeeType(Pointee), Class(Cls) {}
2860 
2861 public:
2862  QualType getPointeeType() const { return PointeeType; }
2863 
2864  /// Returns true if the member type (i.e. the pointee type) is a
2865  /// function type rather than a data-member type.
2866  bool isMemberFunctionPointer() const {
2867  return PointeeType->isFunctionProtoType();
2868  }
2869 
2870  /// Returns true if the member type (i.e. the pointee type) is a
2871  /// data type rather than a function type.

2873  return !PointeeType->isFunctionProtoType();
2874  }

2881

2883  Profile(ID, getPointeeType(), getClass());
2884  }
2885

2888  ID.AddPointer(Pointee.getAsOpaquePtr());
2889  ID.AddPointer(Class);
2890  }
2891 
2892  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
2893  return T->getTypeClass() == MemberPointer;
2894  }

2897 /// Represents an array type, per C99 6.7.5.2 - Array Declarators.
2898 class ArrayType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
2899 public:
2900  /// Capture whether this is a normal array (e.g. int X[4])
2901  /// an array with a static size (e.g. int X[static 4]), or an array
2902  /// with a star size (e.g. int X[*]).
2903  /// 'static' is only allowed on function parameters.
2904  enum ArraySizeModifier {
2905  Normal, Static, Star
2906  };
2907 
2908 private:
2909  /// The element type of the array.
2910  QualType ElementType;
2911 
2912 protected:
2913  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
2914 
2915  ArrayType(TypeClass tc, QualType et, QualType can, ArraySizeModifier sm,
2916  unsigned tq, const Expr *sz = nullptr);
2917 
2918 public:
2919  QualType getElementType() const { return ElementType; }
2920 
2921  ArraySizeModifier getSizeModifier() const {
2922  return ArraySizeModifier(ArrayTypeBits.SizeModifier);
2923  }
2924 
2925  Qualifiers getIndexTypeQualifiers() const {
2926  return Qualifiers::fromCVRMask(getIndexTypeCVRQualifiers());
2927  }
2928 
2929  unsigned getIndexTypeCVRQualifiers() const {
2930  return ArrayTypeBits.IndexTypeQuals;
2931  }
2932 
2933  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
2934  return T->getTypeClass() == ConstantArray ||
2935  T->getTypeClass() == VariableArray ||
2936  T->getTypeClass() == IncompleteArray ||
2937  T->getTypeClass() == DependentSizedArray;
2938  }
2939 };

2941 /// Represents the canonical version of C arrays with a specified constant size.
2942 /// For example, the canonical type for 'int A[4 + 4*100]' is a
2943 /// ConstantArrayType where the element type is 'int' and the size is 404.
2944 class ConstantArrayType final
2945  : public ArrayType,
2946  private llvm::TrailingObjects<ConstantArrayType, const Expr *> {
2947  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
2948  friend TrailingObjects;
2949 
2950  llvm::APInt Size; // Allows us to unique the type.
2951 
2952  ConstantArrayType(QualType et, QualType can, const llvm::APInt &size,
2953  const Expr *sz, ArraySizeModifier sm, unsigned tq)
2954  : ArrayType(ConstantArray, et, can, sm, tq, sz), Size(size) {
2955  ConstantArrayTypeBits.HasStoredSizeExpr = sz != nullptr;
2956  if (ConstantArrayTypeBits.HasStoredSizeExpr) {
2957  assert(!can.isNull() && "canonical constant array should not have size");
2958  *getTrailingObjects<const Expr*>() = sz;
2959  }
2960  }
2961 
2962  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<const Expr*>) const {
2963  return ConstantArrayTypeBits.HasStoredSizeExpr;
2964  }
2965 
2966 public:
2967  const llvm::APInt &getSize() const { return Size; }
2968  const Expr *getSizeExpr() const {
2969  return ConstantArrayTypeBits.HasStoredSizeExpr
2970  ? *getTrailingObjects<const Expr *>()
2971  : nullptr;
2972  }
2973  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
2974  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
2975 
2976  /// Determine the number of bits required to address a member of
2977  // an array with the given element type and number of elements.
2978  static unsigned getNumAddressingBits(const ASTContext &Context,
2979  QualType ElementType,
2980  const llvm::APInt &NumElements);
2981 
2982  /// Determine the maximum number of active bits that an array's size
2983  /// can require, which limits the maximum size of the array.
2984  static unsigned getMaxSizeBits(const ASTContext &Context);
2985 
2986  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, const ASTContext &Ctx) {
2987  Profile(ID, Ctx, getElementType(), getSize(), getSizeExpr(),
2988  getSizeModifier(), getIndexTypeCVRQualifiers());
2989  }
2990 
2991  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, const ASTContext &Ctx,
2992  QualType ET, const llvm::APInt &ArraySize,
2993  const Expr *SizeExpr, ArraySizeModifier SizeMod,
2994  unsigned TypeQuals);
2995 
2996  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
2997  return T->getTypeClass() == ConstantArray;
2998  }
2999 };

3019  }

3034 /// Represents a C array with a specified size that is not an
3035 /// integer-constant-expression. For example, 'int s[x+foo()]'.
3036 /// Since the size expression is an arbitrary expression, we store it as such.
3037 ///
3038 /// Note: VariableArrayType's aren't uniqued (since the expressions aren't) and
3039 /// should not be: two lexically equivalent variable array types could mean
3040 /// different things, for example, these variables do not have the same type
3041 /// dynamically:
3042 ///
3043 /// void foo(int x) {
3044 /// int Y[x];
3045 /// ++x;
3046 /// int Z[x];
3047 /// }
3048 class VariableArrayType : public ArrayType {
3049  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
3050 
3051  /// An assignment-expression. VLA's are only permitted within
3052  /// a function block.
3053  Stmt *SizeExpr;
3054 
3055  /// The range spanned by the left and right array brackets.
3056  SourceRange Brackets;
3057 
3058  VariableArrayType(QualType et, QualType can, Expr *e,
3059  ArraySizeModifier sm, unsigned tq,
3060  SourceRange brackets)
3061  : ArrayType(VariableArray, et, can, sm, tq, e),
3062  SizeExpr((Stmt*) e), Brackets(brackets) {}
3063 
3064 public:
3065  friend class StmtIteratorBase;
3066 
3067  Expr *getSizeExpr() const {
3068  // We use C-style casts instead of cast<> here because we do not wish
3069  // to have a dependency of Type.h on Stmt.h/Expr.h.
3070  return (Expr*) SizeExpr;
3071  }
3072 
3073  SourceRange getBracketsRange() const { return Brackets; }
3074  SourceLocation getLBracketLoc() const { return Brackets.getBegin(); }
3075  SourceLocation getRBracketLoc() const { return Brackets.getEnd(); }
3076 
3077  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
3078  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
3079 
3080  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
3081  return T->getTypeClass() == VariableArray;

3371 public:
3372  static int getPointAccessorIdx(char c) {
3373  switch (c) {
3374  default: return -1;
3375  case 'x': case 'r': return 0;
3376  case 'y': case 'g': return 1;
3377  case 'z': case 'b': return 2;
3378  case 'w': case 'a': return 3;
3379  }
3380  }
3381 
3382  static int getNumericAccessorIdx(char c) {
3383  switch (c) {
3384  default: return -1;
3385  case '0': return 0;
3386  case '1': return 1;
3387  case '2': return 2;
3388  case '3': return 3;
3389  case '4': return 4;
3390  case '5': return 5;
3391  case '6': return 6;
3392  case '7': return 7;
3393  case '8': return 8;
3394  case '9': return 9;
3395  case 'A':
3396  case 'a': return 10;
3397  case 'B':
3398  case 'b': return 11;
3399  case 'C':
3400  case 'c': return 12;
3401  case 'D':
3402  case 'd': return 13;
3403  case 'E':
3404  case 'e': return 14;
3405  case 'F':
3406  case 'f': return 15;
3407  }
3408  }
3409 
3410  static int getAccessorIdx(char c, bool isNumericAccessor) {
3411  if (isNumericAccessor)
3412  return getNumericAccessorIdx(c);
3413  else
3414  return getPointAccessorIdx(c);
3415  }
3416 
3417  bool isAccessorWithinNumElements(char c, bool isNumericAccessor) const {
3418  if (int idx = getAccessorIdx(c, isNumericAccessor)+1)
3419  return unsigned(idx-1) < getNumElements();
3420  return false;
3421  }

3424  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }

3431 /// Represents a matrix type, as defined in the Matrix Types clang extensions.
3432 /// __attribute__((matrix_type(rows, columns))), where "rows" specifies
3433 /// number of rows and "columns" specifies the number of columns.
3434 class MatrixType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {

3445 
3446 public:
3447  /// Returns type of the elements being stored in the matrix
3448  QualType getElementType() const { return ElementType; }
3449 
3450  /// Valid elements types are the following:
3451  /// * an integer type (as in C2x 6.2.5p19), but excluding enumerated types

3455  static bool isValidElementType(QualType T) {
