3559 /// FunctionType - C99 6.7.5.3 - Function Declarators. This is the common base
3560 /// class of FunctionNoProtoType and FunctionProtoType.
3561 class FunctionType : public Type {
3562  // The type returned by the function.
3563  QualType ResultType;
3564 
3565 public:
3566  /// Interesting information about a specific parameter that can't simply
3567  /// be reflected in parameter's type. This is only used by FunctionProtoType
3568  /// but is in FunctionType to make this class available during the
3569  /// specification of the bases of FunctionProtoType.
3570  ///
3571  /// It makes sense to model language features this way when there's some
3572  /// sort of parameter-specific override (such as an attribute) that
3573  /// affects how the function is called. For example, the ARC ns_consumed
3574  /// attribute changes whether a parameter is passed at +0 (the default)
3575  /// or +1 (ns_consumed). This must be reflected in the function type,
3576  /// but isn't really a change to the parameter type.
3577  ///
3578  /// One serious disadvantage of modelling language features this way is
3579  /// that they generally do not work with language features that attempt
3580  /// to destructure types. For example, template argument deduction will
3581  /// not be able to match a parameter declared as
3582  /// T (*)(U)
3583  /// against an argument of type
3584  /// void (*)(__attribute__((ns_consumed)) id)
3585  /// because the substitution of T=void, U=id into the former will
3586  /// not produce the latter.
3587  class ExtParameterInfo {
3588  enum {
3589  ABIMask = 0x0F,
3590  IsConsumed = 0x10,
3591  HasPassObjSize = 0x20,
3592  IsNoEscape = 0x40,
3593  };
3594  unsigned char Data = 0;
3595 
3596  public:
3597  ExtParameterInfo() = default;
3598 
3599  /// Return the ABI treatment of this parameter.
3600  ParameterABI getABI() const { return ParameterABI(Data & ABIMask); }
3601  ExtParameterInfo withABI(ParameterABI kind) const {
3602  ExtParameterInfo copy = *this;
3603  copy.Data = (copy.Data & ~ABIMask) | unsigned(kind);
3604  return copy;
3605  }
3606 
3607  /// Is this parameter considered "consumed" by Objective-C ARC?
3608  /// Consumed parameters must have retainable object type.
3609  bool isConsumed() const { return (Data & IsConsumed); }
3610  ExtParameterInfo withIsConsumed(bool consumed) const {
3611  ExtParameterInfo copy = *this;
3612  if (consumed)
3613  copy.Data |= IsConsumed;
3614  else
3615  copy.Data &= ~IsConsumed;
3616  return copy;
3617  }
3618 
3619  bool hasPassObjectSize() const { return Data & HasPassObjSize; }
3620  ExtParameterInfo withHasPassObjectSize() const {
3621  ExtParameterInfo Copy = *this;
3622  Copy.Data |= HasPassObjSize;
3623  return Copy;
3624  }
3625 
3626  bool isNoEscape() const { return Data & IsNoEscape; }
3627  ExtParameterInfo withIsNoEscape(bool NoEscape) const {
3628  ExtParameterInfo Copy = *this;
3629  if (NoEscape)
3630  Copy.Data |= IsNoEscape;
3631  else
3632  Copy.Data &= ~IsNoEscape;
3633  return Copy;
3634  }
3635 
3636  unsigned char getOpaqueValue() const { return Data; }
3637  static ExtParameterInfo getFromOpaqueValue(unsigned char data) {
3638  ExtParameterInfo result;
3639  result.Data = data;
3640  return result;
3641  }
3642 
3643  friend bool operator==(ExtParameterInfo lhs, ExtParameterInfo rhs) {
3644  return lhs.Data == rhs.Data;
3645  }
3646 
3647  friend bool operator!=(ExtParameterInfo lhs, ExtParameterInfo rhs) {
3648  return lhs.Data != rhs.Data;
3649  }
3650  };
3651 
3652  /// A class which abstracts out some details necessary for
3653  /// making a call.
3654  ///
3655  /// It is not actually used directly for storing this information in
3656  /// a FunctionType, although FunctionType does currently use the
3657  /// same bit-pattern.
3658  ///
3659  // If you add a field (say Foo), other than the obvious places (both,
3660  // constructors, compile failures), what you need to update is
3661  // * Operator==
3662  // * getFoo
3663  // * withFoo
3664  // * functionType. Add Foo, getFoo.
3665  // * ASTContext::getFooType
3666  // * ASTContext::mergeFunctionTypes
3667  // * FunctionNoProtoType::Profile
3668  // * FunctionProtoType::Profile
3669  // * TypePrinter::PrintFunctionProto
3670  // * AST read and write
3671  // * Codegen
3672  class ExtInfo {
3673  friend class FunctionType;
3674 
3675  // Feel free to rearrange or add bits, but if you go over 16, you'll need to
3676  // adjust the Bits field below, and if you add bits, you'll need to adjust
3677  // Type::FunctionTypeBitfields::ExtInfo as well.
3678 
3679  // | CC |noreturn|produces|nocallersavedregs|regparm|nocfcheck|cmsenscall|
3680  // |0 .. 4| 5 | 6 | 7 |8 .. 10| 11 | 12 |
3681  //
3682  // regparm is either 0 (no regparm attribute) or the regparm value+1.
3683  enum { CallConvMask = 0x1F };
3684  enum { NoReturnMask = 0x20 };
3685  enum { ProducesResultMask = 0x40 };
3686  enum { NoCallerSavedRegsMask = 0x80 };
3687  enum {
3688  RegParmMask = 0x700,
3689  RegParmOffset = 8
3690  };
3691  enum { NoCfCheckMask = 0x800 };
3692  enum { CmseNSCallMask = 0x1000 };
3693  uint16_t Bits = CC_C;
3694 
3695  ExtInfo(unsigned Bits) : Bits(static_cast<uint16_t>(Bits)) {}
3696 
3697  public:
3698  // Constructor with no defaults. Use this when you know that you
3699  // have all the elements (when reading an AST file for example).
3700  ExtInfo(bool noReturn, bool hasRegParm, unsigned regParm, CallingConv cc,
3701  bool producesResult, bool noCallerSavedRegs, bool NoCfCheck,
3702  bool cmseNSCall) {
3703  assert((!hasRegParm || regParm < 7) && "Invalid regparm value");
3704  Bits = ((unsigned)cc) | (noReturn ? NoReturnMask : 0) |
3705  (producesResult ? ProducesResultMask : 0) |
3706  (noCallerSavedRegs ? NoCallerSavedRegsMask : 0) |
3707  (hasRegParm ? ((regParm + 1) << RegParmOffset) : 0) |
3708  (NoCfCheck ? NoCfCheckMask : 0) |
3709  (cmseNSCall ? CmseNSCallMask : 0);
3710  }
3711 
3712  // Constructor with all defaults. Use when for example creating a
3713  // function known to use defaults.
3714  ExtInfo() = default;
3715 
3716  // Constructor with just the calling convention, which is an important part
3717  // of the canonical type.
3718  ExtInfo(CallingConv CC) : Bits(CC) {}
3719 
3720  bool getNoReturn() const { return Bits & NoReturnMask; }
3721  bool getProducesResult() const { return Bits & ProducesResultMask; }
3722  bool getCmseNSCall() const { return Bits & CmseNSCallMask; }
3723  bool getNoCallerSavedRegs() const { return Bits & NoCallerSavedRegsMask; }
3724  bool getNoCfCheck() const { return Bits & NoCfCheckMask; }
3725  bool getHasRegParm() const { return ((Bits & RegParmMask) >> RegParmOffset) != 0; }
3726 
3727  unsigned getRegParm() const {
3728  unsigned RegParm = (Bits & RegParmMask) >> RegParmOffset;
3729  if (RegParm > 0)
3730  --RegParm;
3731  return RegParm;
3732  }
3733 
3734  CallingConv getCC() const { return CallingConv(Bits & CallConvMask); }
3735 
3736  bool operator==(ExtInfo Other) const {
3737  return Bits == Other.Bits;
3738  }
3739  bool operator!=(ExtInfo Other) const {
3740  return Bits != Other.Bits;
3741  }
3742 
3743  // Note that we don't have setters. That is by design, use
3744  // the following with methods instead of mutating these objects.
3745 
3746  ExtInfo withNoReturn(bool noReturn) const {
3747  if (noReturn)
3748  return ExtInfo(Bits | NoReturnMask);
3749  else
3750  return ExtInfo(Bits & ~NoReturnMask);
3751  }
3752 
3753  ExtInfo withProducesResult(bool producesResult) const {
3754  if (producesResult)
3755  return ExtInfo(Bits | ProducesResultMask);
3756  else
3757  return ExtInfo(Bits & ~ProducesResultMask);
3758  }
3759 
3760  ExtInfo withCmseNSCall(bool cmseNSCall) const {
3761  if (cmseNSCall)
3762  return ExtInfo(Bits | CmseNSCallMask);
3763  else
3764  return ExtInfo(Bits & ~CmseNSCallMask);
3765  }
3766 
3767  ExtInfo withNoCallerSavedRegs(bool noCallerSavedRegs) const {
3768  if (noCallerSavedRegs)
3769  return ExtInfo(Bits | NoCallerSavedRegsMask);
3770  else
3771  return ExtInfo(Bits & ~NoCallerSavedRegsMask);
3772  }
3773 
3774  ExtInfo withNoCfCheck(bool noCfCheck) const {
3775  if (noCfCheck)
3776  return ExtInfo(Bits | NoCfCheckMask);
3777  else
3778  return ExtInfo(Bits & ~NoCfCheckMask);
3779  }
3780 
3781  ExtInfo withRegParm(unsigned RegParm) const {
3782  assert(RegParm < 7 && "Invalid regparm value");
3783  return ExtInfo((Bits & ~RegParmMask) |
3784  ((RegParm + 1) << RegParmOffset));
3785  }
3786 
3787  ExtInfo withCallingConv(CallingConv cc) const {
3788  return ExtInfo((Bits & ~CallConvMask) | (unsigned) cc);
3789  }
3790 
3791  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) const {
3792  ID.AddInteger(Bits);
3793  }
3794  };
3795 
3796  /// A simple holder for a QualType representing a type in an
3797  /// exception specification. Unfortunately needed by FunctionProtoType
3798  /// because TrailingObjects cannot handle repeated types.
3799  struct ExceptionType { QualType Type; };
3800 
3801  /// A simple holder for various uncommon bits which do not fit in
3802  /// FunctionTypeBitfields. Aligned to alignof(void *) to maintain the
3803  /// alignment of subsequent objects in TrailingObjects. You must update
3804  /// hasExtraBitfields in FunctionProtoType after adding extra data here.
3805  struct alignas(void *) FunctionTypeExtraBitfields {
3806  /// The number of types in the exception specification.
3807  /// A whole unsigned is not needed here and according to
3808  /// [implimits] 8 bits would be enough here.
3809  unsigned NumExceptionType;
3810  };

3835  CallingConv getCallConv() const { return getExtInfo().getCC(); }
3836  ExtInfo getExtInfo() const { return ExtInfo(FunctionTypeBits.ExtInfo); }
3837 
3838  static_assert((~Qualifiers::FastMask & Qualifiers::CVRMask) == 0,
3839  "Const, volatile and restrict are assumed to be a subset of "
3840  "the fast qualifiers.");

3892 
3893 /// Represents a prototype with parameter type info, e.g.
3894 /// 'int foo(int)' or 'int foo(void)'. 'void' is represented as having no
3895 /// parameters, not as having a single void parameter. Such a type can have
3896 /// an exception specification, but this specification is not part of the
3897 /// canonical type. FunctionProtoType has several trailing objects, some of
3898 /// which optional. For more information about the trailing objects see
3899 /// the first comment inside FunctionProtoType.
3900 class FunctionProtoType final
3901  : public FunctionType,
3902  public llvm::FoldingSetNode,
3903  private llvm::TrailingObjects<
3904  FunctionProtoType, QualType, SourceLocation,
3905  FunctionType::FunctionTypeExtraBitfields, FunctionType::ExceptionType,
3906  Expr *, FunctionDecl *, FunctionType::ExtParameterInfo, Qualifiers> {
3907  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
3908  friend TrailingObjects;
3909 
3910  // FunctionProtoType is followed by several trailing objects, some of
3911  // which optional. They are in order:
3912  //
3913  // * An array of getNumParams() QualType holding the parameter types.
3914  // Always present. Note that for the vast majority of FunctionProtoType,
3915  // these will be the only trailing objects.
3916  //
3917  // * Optionally if the function is variadic, the SourceLocation of the
3918  // ellipsis.
3919  //
3920  // * Optionally if some extra data is stored in FunctionTypeExtraBitfields
3921  // (see FunctionTypeExtraBitfields and FunctionTypeBitfields):
3922  // a single FunctionTypeExtraBitfields. Present if and only if
3923  // hasExtraBitfields() is true.
3924  //
3925  // * Optionally exactly one of:
3926  // * an array of getNumExceptions() ExceptionType,
3927  // * a single Expr *,
3928  // * a pair of FunctionDecl *,
3929  // * a single FunctionDecl *
3930  // used to store information about the various types of exception
3931  // specification. See getExceptionSpecSize for the details.
3932  //
3933  // * Optionally an array of getNumParams() ExtParameterInfo holding
3934  // an ExtParameterInfo for each of the parameters. Present if and
3935  // only if hasExtParameterInfos() is true.
3936  //
3937  // * Optionally a Qualifiers object to represent extra qualifiers that can't
3938  // be represented by FunctionTypeBitfields.FastTypeQuals. Present if and only
3939  // if hasExtQualifiers() is true.
3940  //
3941  // The optional FunctionTypeExtraBitfields has to be before the data
3942  // related to the exception specification since it contains the number
3943  // of exception types.
3944  //
3945  // We put the ExtParameterInfos last. If all were equal, it would make
3946  // more sense to put these before the exception specification, because
3947  // it's much easier to skip past them compared to the elaborate switch
3948  // required to skip the exception specification. However, all is not
3949  // equal; ExtParameterInfos are used to model very uncommon features,
3950  // and it's better not to burden the more common paths.
3951 
3952 public:
3953  /// Holds information about the various types of exception specification.
3954  /// ExceptionSpecInfo is not stored as such in FunctionProtoType but is
3955  /// used to group together the various bits of information about the
3956  /// exception specification.
3957  struct ExceptionSpecInfo {
3958  /// The kind of exception specification this is.
3959  ExceptionSpecificationType Type = EST_None;
3960 
3961  /// Explicitly-specified list of exception types.
3962  ArrayRef<QualType> Exceptions;
3963 
3964  /// Noexcept expression, if this is a computed noexcept specification.
3965  Expr *NoexceptExpr = nullptr;
3966 
3967  /// The function whose exception specification this is, for
3968  /// EST_Unevaluated and EST_Uninstantiated.
3969  FunctionDecl *SourceDecl = nullptr;
3970 
3971  /// The function template whose exception specification this is instantiated
3972  /// from, for EST_Uninstantiated.
3973  FunctionDecl *SourceTemplate = nullptr;
3974 
3975  ExceptionSpecInfo() = default;
3976 
3977  ExceptionSpecInfo(ExceptionSpecificationType EST) : Type(EST) {}
3978  };
3979 
3980  /// Extra information about a function prototype. ExtProtoInfo is not
3981  /// stored as such in FunctionProtoType but is used to group together
3982  /// the various bits of extra information about a function prototype.
3983  struct ExtProtoInfo {
3984  FunctionType::ExtInfo ExtInfo;
3985  bool Variadic : 1;
3986  bool HasTrailingReturn : 1;
3987  Qualifiers TypeQuals;
3988  RefQualifierKind RefQualifier = RQ_None;
3989  ExceptionSpecInfo ExceptionSpec;
3990  const ExtParameterInfo *ExtParameterInfos = nullptr;
3991  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc;
3992 
3993  ExtProtoInfo() : Variadic(false), HasTrailingReturn(false) {}
3994 
3995  ExtProtoInfo(CallingConv CC)
3996  : ExtInfo(CC), Variadic(false), HasTrailingReturn(false) {}
3997 
3998  ExtProtoInfo withExceptionSpec(const ExceptionSpecInfo &ESI) {
3999  ExtProtoInfo Result(*this);
4000  Result.ExceptionSpec = ESI;
4001  return Result;
4002  }
4003  };
4004 
4005 private:
4006  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<QualType>) const {
4007  return getNumParams();
4008  }
4009

4011  return isVariadic();
4012  }
4013

4015  return hasExtraBitfields();
4016  }
4017 
4018  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<ExceptionType>) const {
4019  return getExceptionSpecSize().NumExceptionType;
4020  }
4021 
4022  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<Expr *>) const {
4023  return getExceptionSpecSize().NumExprPtr;
4024  }
4025 
4026  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<FunctionDecl *>) const {
4027  return getExceptionSpecSize().NumFunctionDeclPtr;
4028  }
4029

4031  return hasExtParameterInfos() ? getNumParams() : 0;
4032  }

4034  /// Determine whether there are any argument types that
4035  /// contain an unexpanded parameter pack.
4036  static bool containsAnyUnexpandedParameterPack(const QualType *ArgArray,
4037  unsigned numArgs) {
4038  for (unsigned Idx = 0; Idx < numArgs; ++Idx)
4039  if (ArgArray[Idx]->containsUnexpandedParameterPack())
4040  return true;
4041 
4042  return false;
4043  }
4044 
4045  FunctionProtoType(QualType result, ArrayRef<QualType> params,
4046  QualType canonical, const ExtProtoInfo &epi);

4048  /// This struct is returned by getExceptionSpecSize and is used to
4049  /// translate an ExceptionSpecificationType to the number and kind
4050  /// of trailing objects related to the exception specification.
4051  struct ExceptionSpecSizeHolder {
4052  unsigned NumExceptionType;
4053  unsigned NumExprPtr;
4054  unsigned NumFunctionDeclPtr;
4055  };
4056 
4057  /// Return the number and kind of trailing objects
4058  /// related to the exception specification.
4059  static ExceptionSpecSizeHolder
4060  getExceptionSpecSize(ExceptionSpecificationType EST, unsigned NumExceptions) {
4061  switch (EST) {
4062  case EST_None:
4063  case EST_DynamicNone:
4064  case EST_MSAny:
4065  case EST_BasicNoexcept:
4066  case EST_Unparsed:
4067  case EST_NoThrow:
4068  return {0, 0, 0};
4069 
4070  case EST_Dynamic:
4071  return {NumExceptions, 0, 0};
4072 
4073  case EST_DependentNoexcept:
4074  case EST_NoexceptFalse:
4075  case EST_NoexceptTrue:
4076  return {0, 1, 0};
4077 
4078  case EST_Uninstantiated:
4079  return {0, 0, 2};
4080 
4081  case EST_Unevaluated:
4082  return {0, 0, 1};
4083  }
4084  llvm_unreachable("bad exception specification kind");
4085  }
4086 
4087  /// Return the number and kind of trailing objects
4088  /// related to the exception specification.
4089  ExceptionSpecSizeHolder getExceptionSpecSize() const {
4090  return getExceptionSpecSize(getExceptionSpecType(), getNumExceptions());
4091  }
4092 
4093  /// Whether the trailing FunctionTypeExtraBitfields is present.
4094  static bool hasExtraBitfields(ExceptionSpecificationType EST) {
4095  // If the exception spec type is EST_Dynamic then we have > 0 exception
4096  // types and the exact number is stored in FunctionTypeExtraBitfields.
4097  return EST == EST_Dynamic;
4098  }
4099 
4100  /// Whether the trailing FunctionTypeExtraBitfields is present.
4101  bool hasExtraBitfields() const {
4102  return hasExtraBitfields(getExceptionSpecType());
4103  }
4104 
4105  bool hasExtQualifiers() const {
4106  return FunctionTypeBits.HasExtQuals;
4107  }

4110  unsigned getNumParams() const { return FunctionTypeBits.NumParams; }
4111

4119  }

4135  ExceptionSpecificationType getExceptionSpecType() const {
4136  return static_cast<ExceptionSpecificationType>(
4137  FunctionTypeBits.ExceptionSpecType);
4138  }

4140  /// Return whether this function has any kind of exception spec.
4141  bool hasExceptionSpec() const { return getExceptionSpecType() != EST_None; }
4142

4157  /// spec.

4160  /// Return all the available information about this type's exception spec.
4161  ExceptionSpecInfo getExceptionSpecInfo() const {
4162  ExceptionSpecInfo Result;
4163  Result.Type = getExceptionSpecType();
4164  if (Result.Type == EST_Dynamic) {
4165  Result.Exceptions = exceptions();
4166  } else if (isComputedNoexcept(Result.Type)) {
4167  Result.NoexceptExpr = getNoexceptExpr();
4168  } else if (Result.Type == EST_Uninstantiated) {
4169  Result.SourceDecl = getExceptionSpecDecl();
4170  Result.SourceTemplate = getExceptionSpecTemplate();
4171  } else if (Result.Type == EST_Unevaluated) {
4172  Result.SourceDecl = getExceptionSpecDecl();
4173  }
4174  return Result;
4175  }
4176 
4177  /// Return the number of types in the exception specification.
4178  unsigned getNumExceptions() const {
4179  return getExceptionSpecType() == EST_Dynamic
4180  ? getTrailingObjects<FunctionTypeExtraBitfields>()
4181  ->NumExceptionType
4182  : 0;
4183  }

4186  QualType getExceptionType(unsigned i) const {
4187  assert(i < getNumExceptions() && "Invalid exception number!");
4188  return exception_begin()[i];
4189  }

4192  /// if there is none (because the exception spec is not of this form).
4193  Expr *getNoexceptExpr() const {
4194  if (!isComputedNoexcept(getExceptionSpecType()))
4195  return nullptr;

4197  }

4199  /// If this function type has an exception specification which hasn't
4200  /// been determined yet (either because it has not been evaluated or because
4201  /// it has not been instantiated), this is the function whose exception
4202  /// specification is represented by this type.

4204  if (getExceptionSpecType() != EST_Uninstantiated &&
4205  getExceptionSpecType() != EST_Unevaluated)
4206  return nullptr;
4207  return getTrailingObjects<FunctionDecl *>()[0];

4216  return nullptr;

4218  }

4360 
4361  UnresolvedUsingType(const UnresolvedUsingTypenameDecl *D)

4692 /// An attributed type is a type to which a type attribute has been applied.
4693 ///
4694 /// The "modified type" is the fully-sugared type to which the attributed
4695 /// type was applied; generally it is not canonically equivalent to the
4696 /// attributed type. The "equivalent type" is the minimally-desugared type
4697 /// which the type is canonically equivalent to.
4698 ///
4699 /// For example, in the following attributed type:
4700 /// int32_t __attribute__((vector_size(16)))
4701 /// - the modified type is the TypedefType for int32_t
4702 /// - the equivalent type is VectorType(16, int32_t)
4703 /// - the canonical type is VectorType(16, int)
4704 class AttributedType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
4705 public:
4706  using Kind = attr::Kind;
4707 
4708 private:
4709  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
4710 
4711  QualType ModifiedType;
4712  QualType EquivalentType;
4713 
4714  AttributedType(QualType canon, attr::Kind attrKind, QualType modified,
4715  QualType equivalent)
4716  : Type(Attributed, canon, equivalent->getDependence()),
4717  ModifiedType(modified), EquivalentType(equivalent) {
4718  AttributedTypeBits.AttrKind = attrKind;
4719  }
4720 
4721 public:
4722  Kind getAttrKind() const {
4723  return static_cast<Kind>(AttributedTypeBits.AttrKind);
4724  }
4725 
4726  QualType getModifiedType() const { return ModifiedType; }
4727  QualType getEquivalentType() const { return EquivalentType; }
4728 
4729  bool isSugared() const { return true; }
4730  QualType desugar() const { return getEquivalentType(); }
4731 
4732  /// Does this attribute behave like a type qualifier?
4733  ///
4734  /// A type qualifier adjusts a type to provide specialized rules for
4735  /// a specific object, like the standard const and volatile qualifiers.
4736  /// This includes attributes controlling things like nullability,
4737  /// address spaces, and ARC ownership. The value of the object is still
4738  /// largely described by the modified type.
4739  ///
4740  /// In contrast, many type attributes "rewrite" their modified type to
4741  /// produce a fundamentally different type, not necessarily related in any
4742  /// formalizable way to the original type. For example, calling convention
4743  /// and vector attributes are not simple type qualifiers.
4744  ///
4745  /// Type qualifiers are often, but not always, reflected in the canonical
4746  /// type.
4747  bool isQualifier() const;
4748 
4749  bool isMSTypeSpec() const;
4750 
4751  bool isCallingConv() const;
4752 
4753  llvm::Optional<NullabilityKind> getImmediateNullability() const;
4754 
4755  /// Retrieve the attribute kind corresponding to the given
4756  /// nullability kind.
4757  static Kind getNullabilityAttrKind(NullabilityKind kind) {
4758  switch (kind) {
4759  case NullabilityKind::NonNull:
4760  return attr::TypeNonNull;
4761 
4762  case NullabilityKind::Nullable:
4763  return attr::TypeNullable;
4764 
4765  case NullabilityKind::NullableResult:
4766  return attr::TypeNullableResult;
4767 
4768  case NullabilityKind::Unspecified:
4769  return attr::TypeNullUnspecified;
4770  }
4771  llvm_unreachable("Unknown nullability kind.");
4772  }
4773 
4774  /// Strip off the top-level nullability annotation on the given
4775  /// type, if it's there.
4776  ///
4777  /// \param T The type to strip. If the type is exactly an
4778  /// AttributedType specifying nullability (without looking through
4779  /// type sugar), the nullability is returned and this type changed
4780  /// to the underlying modified type.
4781  ///
4782  /// \returns the top-level nullability, if present.
4783  static Optional<NullabilityKind> stripOuterNullability(QualType &T);
4784 
4785  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
4786  Profile(ID, getAttrKind(), ModifiedType, EquivalentType);
4787  }
4788 
4789  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, Kind attrKind,
4790  QualType modified, QualType equivalent) {
4791  ID.AddInteger(attrKind);
4792  ID.AddPointer(modified.getAsOpaquePtr());
4793  ID.AddPointer(equivalent.getAsOpaquePtr());
4794  }
4795 
4796  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
4797  return T->getTypeClass() == Attributed;
4798  }
4799 };
4800

4802 private:

4804

4813 public:

4815  const BTFTypeTagAttr *getAttr() const { return BTFAttr; }

4819 
4820  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {

4823

4835 class TemplateTypeParmType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
4836  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
4837 
4838  // Helper data collector for canonical types.
4839  struct CanonicalTTPTInfo {
4840  unsigned Depth : 15;
4841  unsigned ParameterPack : 1;
4842  unsigned Index : 16;
4843  };
4844 
4845  union {
4846  // Info for the canonical type.
4847  CanonicalTTPTInfo CanTTPTInfo;
4848 
4849  // Info for the non-canonical type.
4850  TemplateTypeParmDecl *TTPDecl;
4851  };
4852 
4853  /// Build a non-canonical type.
4854  TemplateTypeParmType(TemplateTypeParmDecl *TTPDecl, QualType Canon)
4855  : Type(TemplateTypeParm, Canon,
4856  TypeDependence::DependentInstantiation |
4857  (Canon->getDependence() & TypeDependence::UnexpandedPack)),
4858  TTPDecl(TTPDecl) {}
4859 
4860  /// Build the canonical type.
4861  TemplateTypeParmType(unsigned D, unsigned I, bool PP)
4862  : Type(TemplateTypeParm, QualType(this, 0),
4863  TypeDependence::DependentInstantiation |
4864  (PP ? TypeDependence::UnexpandedPack : TypeDependence::None)) {
4865  CanTTPTInfo.Depth = D;
4866  CanTTPTInfo.Index = I;
4867  CanTTPTInfo.ParameterPack = PP;
4868  }
4869 
4870  const CanonicalTTPTInfo& getCanTTPTInfo() const {
4871  QualType Can = getCanonicalTypeInternal();
4872  return Can->castAs<TemplateTypeParmType>()->CanTTPTInfo;
4873  }
4874 
4875 public:
4876  unsigned getDepth() const { return getCanTTPTInfo().Depth; }
4877  unsigned getIndex() const { return getCanTTPTInfo().Index; }
4878  bool isParameterPack() const { return getCanTTPTInfo().ParameterPack; }
4879 
4880  TemplateTypeParmDecl *getDecl() const {
4881  return isCanonicalUnqualified() ? nullptr : TTPDecl;
4882  }
4883 
4884  IdentifierInfo *getIdentifier() const;
4885 
4886  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
4887  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
4888 
4889  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
4890  Profile(ID, getDepth(), getIndex(), isParameterPack(), getDecl());
4891  }
4892 
4893  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, unsigned Depth,
4894  unsigned Index, bool ParameterPack,
4895  TemplateTypeParmDecl *TTPDecl) {
4896  ID.AddInteger(Depth);
4897  ID.AddInteger(Index);
4898  ID.AddBoolean(ParameterPack);
4899  ID.AddPointer(TTPDecl);
4900  }
4901 
4902  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
4903  return T->getTypeClass() == TemplateTypeParm;
4904  }
4905 };

4907 /// Represents the result of substituting a type for a template
4908 /// type parameter.
4909 ///
4910 /// Within an instantiated template, all template type parameters have
4911 /// been replaced with these. They are used solely to record that a
4912 /// type was originally written as a template type parameter;
4913 /// therefore they are never canonical.
4914 class SubstTemplateTypeParmType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {

4927  return Replaced;
4928  }
4929

4931  /// parameter.
4932  QualType getReplacementType() const {
4933  return getCanonicalTypeInternal();
4934  }

4937  QualType desugar() const { return getReplacementType(); }
4938

4940  Profile(ID, getReplacedParameter(), getReplacementType());
4941  }
4942 
4943  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
4944  const TemplateTypeParmType *Replaced,

4947  ID.AddPointer(Replacement.getAsOpaquePtr());
4948  }

4951  return T->getTypeClass() == SubstTemplateTypeParm;
4952  }

4983

4985  const TemplateTypeParmType *getReplacedParameter() const {
4986  return Replaced;
4987  }

4990  return SubstTemplateTypeParmPackTypeBits.NumArgs;
4991  }
4992

4995 
4996  TemplateArgument getArgumentPack() const;
4997 
4998  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID);
4999  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
5000  const TemplateTypeParmType *Replaced,
5001  const TemplateArgument &ArgPack);
5002

5004  return T->getTypeClass() == SubstTemplateTypeParmPack;

5008 /// Common base class for placeholders for types that get replaced by
5009 /// placeholder type deduction: C++11 auto, C++14 decltype(auto), C++17 deduced
5010 /// class template types, and constrained type names.
5011 ///
5012 /// These types are usually a placeholder for a deduced type. However, before
5013 /// the initializer is attached, or (usually) if the initializer is
5014 /// type-dependent, there is no deduced type and the type is canonical. In
5015 /// the latter case, it is also a dependent type.
5016 class DeducedType : public Type {
5017  QualType DeducedAsType;
5018 
5019 protected:
5020  DeducedType(TypeClass TC, QualType DeducedAsType,
5021  TypeDependence ExtraDependence, QualType Canon)
5022  : Type(TC, Canon,
5023  ExtraDependence | (DeducedAsType.isNull()
5024  ? TypeDependence::None
5025  : DeducedAsType->getDependence() &
5026  ~TypeDependence::VariablyModified)),
5027  DeducedAsType(DeducedAsType) {}
5028 
5029 public:
5030  bool isSugared() const { return !DeducedAsType.isNull(); }
5031  QualType desugar() const {
5032  return isSugared() ? DeducedAsType : QualType(this, 0);
5033  }
5034 
5035  /// Get the type deduced for this placeholder type, or null if it
5036  /// has not been deduced.
5037  QualType getDeducedType() const { return DeducedAsType; }
5038  bool isDeduced() const {
5039  return !DeducedAsType.isNull() || isDependentType();
5040  }
5041 
5042  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
5043  return T->getTypeClass() == Auto ||
5044  T->getTypeClass() == DeducedTemplateSpecialization;
5045  }
5046 };

5119 /// Represents a C++17 deduced template specialization type.
5120 class DeducedTemplateSpecializationType : public DeducedType,
5121  public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
5122  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
5123 
5124  /// The name of the template whose arguments will be deduced.
5125  TemplateName Template;
5126 
5127  DeducedTemplateSpecializationType(TemplateName Template,
5128  QualType DeducedAsType,
5129  bool IsDeducedAsDependent)
5130  : DeducedType(DeducedTemplateSpecialization, DeducedAsType,
5131  toTypeDependence(Template.getDependence()) |
5132  (IsDeducedAsDependent
5133  ? TypeDependence::DependentInstantiation
5134  : TypeDependence::None),
5135  DeducedAsType.isNull() ? QualType(this, 0)
5136  : DeducedAsType.getCanonicalType()),

5141  TemplateName getTemplateName() const { return Template;}
5142 
5143  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
5144  Profile(ID, getTemplateName(), getDeducedType(), isDependentType());
5145  }
5146 
5147  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, TemplateName Template,
5148  QualType Deduced, bool IsDependent) {
5149  Template.Profile(ID);
5150  QualType CanonicalType =
5151  Deduced.isNull() ? Deduced : Deduced.getCanonicalType();
5152  ID.AddPointer(CanonicalType.getAsOpaquePtr());
5153  ID.AddBoolean(IsDependent || Template.isDependent());
5154  }
5155

5161 /// Represents a type template specialization; the template
5162 /// must be a class template, a type alias template, or a template
5163 /// template parameter. A template which cannot be resolved to one of
5164 /// these, e.g. because it is written with a dependent scope
5165 /// specifier, is instead represented as a
5166 /// @c DependentTemplateSpecializationType.
5167 ///
5168 /// A non-dependent template specialization type is always "sugar",
5169 /// typically for a \c RecordType. For example, a class template
5170 /// specialization type of \c vector<int> will refer to a tag type for
5171 /// the instantiation \c std::vector<int, std::allocator<int>>
5172 ///
5173 /// Template specializations are dependent if either the template or
5174 /// any of the template arguments are dependent, in which case the
5175 /// type may also be canonical.
5176 ///
5177 /// Instances of this type are allocated with a trailing array of
5178 /// TemplateArguments, followed by a QualType representing the
5179 /// non-canonical aliased type when the template is a type alias
5180 /// template.
5181 class alignas(8) TemplateSpecializationType
5182  : public Type,
5183  public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
5184  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
5185 
5186  /// The name of the template being specialized. This is
5187  /// either a TemplateName::Template (in which case it is a
5188  /// ClassTemplateDecl*, a TemplateTemplateParmDecl*, or a
5189  /// TypeAliasTemplateDecl*), a
5190  /// TemplateName::SubstTemplateTemplateParmPack, or a
5191  /// TemplateName::SubstTemplateTemplateParm (in which case the
5192  /// replacement must, recursively, be one of these).
5193  TemplateName Template;
5194 
5195  TemplateSpecializationType(TemplateName T,
5196  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Args,
5197  QualType Canon,
5198  QualType Aliased);
5199 
5200 public:
5201  /// Determine whether any of the given template arguments are dependent.
5202  ///
5203  /// The converted arguments should be supplied when known; whether an
5204  /// argument is dependent can depend on the conversions performed on it
5205  /// (for example, a 'const int' passed as a template argument might be
5206  /// dependent if the parameter is a reference but non-dependent if the
5207  /// parameter is an int).
5208  ///
5209  /// Note that the \p Args parameter is unused: this is intentional, to remind
5210  /// the caller that they need to pass in the converted arguments, not the
5211  /// specified arguments.
5212  static bool
5213  anyDependentTemplateArguments(ArrayRef<TemplateArgumentLoc> Args,
5214  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Converted);
5215  static bool
5216  anyDependentTemplateArguments(const TemplateArgumentListInfo &,
5217  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Converted);
5218  static bool anyInstantiationDependentTemplateArguments(
5219  ArrayRef<TemplateArgumentLoc> Args);
5220 
5221  /// True if this template specialization type matches a current
5222  /// instantiation in the context in which it is found.
5223  bool isCurrentInstantiation() const {
5224  return isa<InjectedClassNameType>(getCanonicalTypeInternal());
5225  }
5226 
5227  /// Determine if this template specialization type is for a type alias
5228  /// template that has been substituted.
5229  ///
5230  /// Nearly every template specialization type whose template is an alias
5231  /// template will be substituted. However, this is not the case when
5232  /// the specialization contains a pack expansion but the template alias
5233  /// does not have a corresponding parameter pack, e.g.,
5234  ///
5235  /// \code
5236  /// template<typename T, typename U, typename V> struct S;
5237  /// template<typename T, typename U> using A = S<T, int, U>;
5238  /// template<typename... Ts> struct X {
5239  /// typedef A<Ts...> type; // not a type alias
5240  /// };
5241  /// \endcode
5242  bool isTypeAlias() const { return TemplateSpecializationTypeBits.TypeAlias; }
5243 
5244  /// Get the aliased type, if this is a specialization of a type alias
5245  /// template.
5246  QualType getAliasedType() const {
5247  assert(isTypeAlias() && "not a type alias template specialization");
5248  return *reinterpret_cast<const QualType*>(end());
5249  }
5250 
5251  using iterator = const TemplateArgument *;
5252 
5253  iterator begin() const { return getArgs(); }
5254  iterator end() const; // defined inline in TemplateBase.h
5255 
5256  /// Retrieve the name of the template that we are specializing.
5257  TemplateName getTemplateName() const { return Template; }
5258 
5259  /// Retrieve the template arguments.
5260  const TemplateArgument *getArgs() const {
5261  return reinterpret_cast<const TemplateArgument *>(this + 1);
5262  }
5263 
5264  /// Retrieve the number of template arguments.
5265  unsigned getNumArgs() const {
5266  return TemplateSpecializationTypeBits.NumArgs;
5267  }
5268 
5269  /// Retrieve a specific template argument as a type.
5270  /// \pre \c isArgType(Arg)
5271  const TemplateArgument &getArg(unsigned Idx) const; // in TemplateBase.h
5272 
5273  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> template_arguments() const {
5274  return {getArgs(), getNumArgs()};
5275  }
5276 
5277  bool isSugared() const {
5278  return !isDependentType() || isCurrentInstantiation() || isTypeAlias();
5279  }
5280 
5281  QualType desugar() const {
5282  return isTypeAlias() ? getAliasedType() : getCanonicalTypeInternal();
5283  }
5284 
5285  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, const ASTContext &Ctx) {
5286  Profile(ID, Template, template_arguments(), Ctx);
5287  if (isTypeAlias())
5288  getAliasedType().Profile(ID);
5289  }
5290 
5291  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, TemplateName T,
5292  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Args,
5293  const ASTContext &Context);
5294 
5295  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
5296  return T->getTypeClass() == TemplateSpecialization;
5297  }
5298 };

5300 /// Print a template argument list, including the '<' and '>'
5301 /// enclosing the template arguments.
5302 void printTemplateArgumentList(raw_ostream &OS,
5303  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Args,
5304  const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
5305  const TemplateParameterList *TPL = nullptr);
5306 
5307 void printTemplateArgumentList(raw_ostream &OS,
5308  ArrayRef<TemplateArgumentLoc> Args,
5309  const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
5310  const TemplateParameterList *TPL = nullptr);

5313  const TemplateArgumentListInfo &Args,
5314  const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
5315  const TemplateParameterList *TPL = nullptr);

5317 /// The injected class name of a C++ class template or class
5318 /// template partial specialization. Used to record that a type was
5319 /// spelled with a bare identifier rather than as a template-id; the
5320 /// equivalent for non-templated classes is just RecordType.
5321 ///
5322 /// Injected class name types are always dependent. Template
5323 /// instantiation turns these into RecordTypes.
5324 ///
5325 /// Injected class name types are always canonical. This works
5326 /// because it is impossible to compare an injected class name type
5327 /// with the corresponding non-injected template type, for the same
5328 /// reason that it is impossible to directly compare template
5329 /// parameters from different dependent contexts: injected class name
5330 /// types can only occur within the scope of a particular templated
5331 /// declaration, and within that scope every template specialization
5332 /// will canonicalize to the injected class name (when appropriate
5333 /// according to the rules of the language).
5334 class InjectedClassNameType : public Type {
5335  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
5336  friend class ASTNodeImporter;
5337  friend class ASTReader; // FIXME: ASTContext::getInjectedClassNameType is not
5338  // currently suitable for AST reading, too much
5339  // interdependencies.
5340  template <class T> friend class serialization::AbstractTypeReader;
5341 
5342  CXXRecordDecl *Decl;
5343 
5344  /// The template specialization which this type represents.
5345  /// For example, in
5346  /// template <class T> class A { ... };
5347  /// this is A<T>, whereas in
5348  /// template <class X, class Y> class A<B<X,Y> > { ... };
5349  /// this is A<B<X,Y> >.
5350  ///
5351  /// It is always unqualified, always a template specialization type,
5352  /// and always dependent.
5353  QualType InjectedType;
5354 
5355  InjectedClassNameType(CXXRecordDecl *D, QualType TST)
5356  : Type(InjectedClassName, QualType(),
5357  TypeDependence::DependentInstantiation),
5358  Decl(D), InjectedType(TST) {
5359  assert(isa<TemplateSpecializationType>(TST));
5360  assert(!TST.hasQualifiers());
5361  assert(TST->isDependentType());
5362  }
5363 
5364 public:
5365  QualType getInjectedSpecializationType() const { return InjectedType; }
5366 
5367  const TemplateSpecializationType *getInjectedTST() const {
5368  return cast<TemplateSpecializationType>(InjectedType.getTypePtr());
5369  }
5370 
5371  TemplateName getTemplateName() const {
5372  return getInjectedTST()->getTemplateName();
5373  }
5374 
5375  CXXRecordDecl *getDecl() const;
5376 
5377  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
5378  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
5379 
5380  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
5381  return T->getTypeClass() == InjectedClassName;
5382  }
5383 };

5388  TTK_Struct,
5389 
5390  /// The "__interface" keyword.
5391  TTK_Interface,
5392 
5393  /// The "union" keyword.
5394  TTK_Union,

5396  /// The "class" keyword.

5399  /// The "enum" keyword.
5400  TTK_Enum

5403 /// The elaboration keyword that precedes a qualified type name or
5404 /// introduces an elaborated-type-specifier.
5405 enum ElaboratedTypeKeyword {
5406  /// The "struct" keyword introduces the elaborated-type-specifier.
5407  ETK_Struct,
5408 
5409  /// The "__interface" keyword introduces the elaborated-type-specifier.
5410  ETK_Interface,
5411 
5412  /// The "union" keyword introduces the elaborated-type-specifier.
5413  ETK_Union,
5414 
5415  /// The "class" keyword introduces the elaborated-type-specifier.
5416  ETK_Class,
5417 
5418  /// The "enum" keyword introduces the elaborated-type-specifier.
5419  ETK_Enum,
5420 
5421  /// The "typename" keyword precedes the qualified type name, e.g.,
5422  /// \c typename T::type.
5423  ETK_Typename,
5424 
5425  /// No keyword precedes the qualified type name.
5426  ETK_None
5427 };

5444  }

5448

5451  static TagTypeKind getTagTypeKindForTypeSpec(unsigned TypeSpec);
5452

5473 /// Represents a type that was referred to using an elaborated type
5474 /// keyword, e.g., struct S, or via a qualified name, e.g., N::M::type,
5475 /// or both.
5476 ///
5477 /// This type is used to keep track of a type name as written in the
5478 /// source code, including tag keywords and any nested-name-specifiers.
5479 /// The type itself is always "sugar", used to express what was written
5480 /// in the source code but containing no additional semantic information.
5481 class ElaboratedType final
5482  : public TypeWithKeyword,
5483  public llvm::FoldingSetNode,
5484  private llvm::TrailingObjects<ElaboratedType, TagDecl *> {
5485  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
5486  friend TrailingObjects;
5487 
5488  /// The nested name specifier containing the qualifier.
5489  NestedNameSpecifier *NNS;
5490 
5491  /// The type that this qualified name refers to.
5492  QualType NamedType;
5493 
5494  /// The (re)declaration of this tag type owned by this occurrence is stored
5495  /// as a trailing object if there is one. Use getOwnedTagDecl to obtain
5496  /// it, or obtain a null pointer if there is none.
5497 
5498  ElaboratedType(ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword, NestedNameSpecifier *NNS,
5499  QualType NamedType, QualType CanonType, TagDecl *OwnedTagDecl)
5500  : TypeWithKeyword(Keyword, Elaborated, CanonType,
5501  // Any semantic dependence on the qualifier will have
5502  // been incorporated into NamedType. We still need to
5503  // track syntactic (instantiation / error / pack)
5504  // dependence on the qualifier.
5505  NamedType->getDependence() |
5506  (NNS ? toSyntacticDependence(
5507  toTypeDependence(NNS->getDependence()))
5508  : TypeDependence::None)),
5509  NNS(NNS), NamedType(NamedType) {
5510  ElaboratedTypeBits.HasOwnedTagDecl = false;
5511  if (OwnedTagDecl) {
5512  ElaboratedTypeBits.HasOwnedTagDecl = true;
5513  *getTrailingObjects<TagDecl *>() = OwnedTagDecl;
5514  }
5515  assert(!(Keyword == ETK_None && NNS == nullptr) &&
5516  "ElaboratedType cannot have elaborated type keyword "
5517  "and name qualifier both null.");
5518  }
5519 
5520 public:
5521  /// Retrieve the qualification on this type.
5522  NestedNameSpecifier *getQualifier() const { return NNS; }
5523 
5524  /// Retrieve the type named by the qualified-id.
5525  QualType getNamedType() const { return NamedType; }
5526 
5527  /// Remove a single level of sugar.
5528  QualType desugar() const { return getNamedType(); }
5529 
5530  /// Returns whether this type directly provides sugar.
5531  bool isSugared() const { return true; }
5532 
5533  /// Return the (re)declaration of this type owned by this occurrence of this
5534  /// type, or nullptr if there is none.
5535  TagDecl *getOwnedTagDecl() const {
5536  return ElaboratedTypeBits.HasOwnedTagDecl ? *getTrailingObjects<TagDecl *>()
5537  : nullptr;
5538  }
5539 
5540  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
5541  Profile(ID, getKeyword(), NNS, NamedType, getOwnedTagDecl());
5542  }
5543 
5544  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword,
5545  NestedNameSpecifier *NNS, QualType NamedType,
5546  TagDecl *OwnedTagDecl) {
5547  ID.AddInteger(Keyword);
5548  ID.AddPointer(NNS);
5549  NamedType.Profile(ID);
5550  ID.AddPointer(OwnedTagDecl);
5551  }
5552 
5553  static bool classof(const Type *T) { return T->getTypeClass() == Elaborated; }
5554 };

5556 /// Represents a qualified type name for which the type name is
5557 /// dependent.
5558 ///
5559 /// DependentNameType represents a class of dependent types that involve a
5560 /// possibly dependent nested-name-specifier (e.g., "T::") followed by a
5561 /// name of a type. The DependentNameType may start with a "typename" (for a
5562 /// typename-specifier), "class", "struct", "union", or "enum" (for a
5563 /// dependent elaborated-type-specifier), or nothing (in contexts where we
5564 /// know that we must be referring to a type, e.g., in a base class specifier).
5565 /// Typically the nested-name-specifier is dependent, but in MSVC compatibility
5566 /// mode, this type is used with non-dependent names to delay name lookup until
5567 /// instantiation.
5568 class DependentNameType : public TypeWithKeyword, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
5569  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
5570 
5571  /// The nested name specifier containing the qualifier.
5572  NestedNameSpecifier *NNS;
5573 
5574  /// The type that this typename specifier refers to.
5575  const IdentifierInfo *Name;
5576 
5577  DependentNameType(ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword, NestedNameSpecifier *NNS,
5578  const IdentifierInfo *Name, QualType CanonType)
5579  : TypeWithKeyword(Keyword, DependentName, CanonType,
5580  TypeDependence::DependentInstantiation |
5581  toTypeDependence(NNS->getDependence())),
5582  NNS(NNS), Name(Name) {}
5583 
5584 public:
5585  /// Retrieve the qualification on this type.
5586  NestedNameSpecifier *getQualifier() const { return NNS; }
5587 
5588  /// Retrieve the type named by the typename specifier as an identifier.
5589  ///
5590  /// This routine will return a non-NULL identifier pointer when the
5591  /// form of the original typename was terminated by an identifier,
5592  /// e.g., "typename T::type".
5593  const IdentifierInfo *getIdentifier() const {
5594  return Name;
5595  }
5596 
5597  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
5598  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
5599 
5600  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
5601  Profile(ID, getKeyword(), NNS, Name);
5602  }
5603 
5604  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword,
5605  NestedNameSpecifier *NNS, const IdentifierInfo *Name) {
5606  ID.AddInteger(Keyword);
5607  ID.AddPointer(NNS);
5608  ID.AddPointer(Name);
5609  }
5610 
5611  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
5612  return T->getTypeClass() == DependentName;
5613  }
5614 };

5616 /// Represents a template specialization type whose template cannot be

5619 class alignas(8) DependentTemplateSpecializationType

5629 
5630  DependentTemplateSpecializationType(ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword,

5634  QualType Canon);

5647 
5648  /// Retrieve the template arguments.
5649  const TemplateArgument *getArgs() const {
5650  return getArgBuffer();
5651  }
5652 
5653  /// Retrieve the number of template arguments.
5654  unsigned getNumArgs() const {
5655  return DependentTemplateSpecializationTypeBits.NumArgs;
5656  }
5657 
5658  const TemplateArgument &getArg(unsigned Idx) const; // in TemplateBase.h
5659 
5660  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> template_arguments() const {
5661  return {getArgs(), getNumArgs()};
5662  }
5663 
5664  using iterator = const TemplateArgument *;
5665 
5666  iterator begin() const { return getArgs(); }
5667  iterator end() const; // inline in TemplateBase.h
5668 
5669  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
5670  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
5671 
5672  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, const ASTContext &Context) {
5673  Profile(ID, Context, getKeyword(), NNS, Name, {getArgs(), getNumArgs()});
5674  }
5675 
5676  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
5677  const ASTContext &Context,
5678  ElaboratedTypeKeyword Keyword,
5679  NestedNameSpecifier *Qualifier,
5680  const IdentifierInfo *Name,
5681  ArrayRef<TemplateArgument> Args);
5682 
5683  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
5684  return T->getTypeClass() == DependentTemplateSpecialization;
5685  }
5686 };
5687 
5688 /// Represents a pack expansion of types.
5689 ///
5690 /// Pack expansions are part of C++11 variadic templates. A pack
5691 /// expansion contains a pattern, which itself contains one or more
5692 /// "unexpanded" parameter packs. When instantiated, a pack expansion
5693 /// produces a series of types, each instantiated from the pattern of
5694 /// the expansion, where the Ith instantiation of the pattern uses the
5695 /// Ith arguments bound to each of the unexpanded parameter packs. The
5696 /// pack expansion is considered to "expand" these unexpanded
5697 /// parameter packs.
5698 ///
5699 /// \code
5700 /// template<typename ...Types> struct tuple;
5701 ///
5702 /// template<typename ...Types>
5703 /// struct tuple_of_references {
5704 /// typedef tuple<Types&...> type;
5705 /// };
5706 /// \endcode
5707 ///
5708 /// Here, the pack expansion \c Types&... is represented via a
5709 /// PackExpansionType whose pattern is Types&.
5710 class PackExpansionType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
5711  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these
5712 
5713  /// The pattern of the pack expansion.
5714  QualType Pattern;
5715 
5716  PackExpansionType(QualType Pattern, QualType Canon,
5717  Optional<unsigned> NumExpansions)
5718  : Type(PackExpansion, Canon,
5719  (Pattern->getDependence() | TypeDependence::Dependent |
5720  TypeDependence::Instantiation) &
5721  ~TypeDependence::UnexpandedPack),
5722  Pattern(Pattern) {
5723  PackExpansionTypeBits.NumExpansions =
5724  NumExpansions ? *NumExpansions + 1 : 0;
5725  }
5726 
5727 public:
5728  /// Retrieve the pattern of this pack expansion, which is the
5729  /// type that will be repeatedly instantiated when instantiating the
5730  /// pack expansion itself.
5731  QualType getPattern() const { return Pattern; }
5732 
5733  /// Retrieve the number of expansions that this pack expansion will
5734  /// generate, if known.
5735  Optional<unsigned> getNumExpansions() const {
5736  if (PackExpansionTypeBits.NumExpansions)
5737  return PackExpansionTypeBits.NumExpansions - 1;
5738  return None;
5739  }
5740 
5741  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
5742  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
5743 
5744  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
5745  Profile(ID, getPattern(), getNumExpansions());
5746  }
5747 
5748  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, QualType Pattern,
5749  Optional<unsigned> NumExpansions) {
5750  ID.AddPointer(Pattern.getAsOpaquePtr());
5751  ID.AddBoolean(NumExpansions.hasValue());
5752  if (NumExpansions)
5753  ID.AddInteger(*NumExpansions);
5754  }
5755 
5756  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
5757  return T->getTypeClass() == PackExpansion;
5758  }
5759 };
5760 
5761 /// This class wraps the list of protocol qualifiers. For types that can
5762 /// take ObjC protocol qualifers, they can subclass this class.
5763 template <class T>
5764 class ObjCProtocolQualifiers {
5765 protected:
5766  ObjCProtocolQualifiers() = default;
5767 
5768  ObjCProtocolDecl * const *getProtocolStorage() const {
5769  return const_cast<ObjCProtocolQualifiers*>(this)->getProtocolStorage();
5770  }
5771 
5772  ObjCProtocolDecl **getProtocolStorage() {
5773  return static_cast<T*>(this)->getProtocolStorageImpl();
5774  }
5775 
5776  void setNumProtocols(unsigned N) {
5777  static_cast<T*>(this)->setNumProtocolsImpl(N);
5778  }
5779 
5780  void initialize(ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols) {
5781  setNumProtocols(protocols.size());
5782  assert(getNumProtocols() == protocols.size() &&
5783  "bitfield overflow in protocol count");
5784  if (!protocols.empty())
5785  memcpy(getProtocolStorage(), protocols.data(),
5786  protocols.size() * sizeof(ObjCProtocolDecl*));
5787  }
5788 
5789 public:
5790  using qual_iterator = ObjCProtocolDecl * const *;
5791  using qual_range = llvm::iterator_range<qual_iterator>;
5792 
5793  qual_range quals() const { return qual_range(qual_begin(), qual_end()); }
5794  qual_iterator qual_begin() const { return getProtocolStorage(); }
5795  qual_iterator qual_end() const { return qual_begin() + getNumProtocols(); }
5796 
5797  bool qual_empty() const { return getNumProtocols() == 0; }
5798 
5799  /// Return the number of qualifying protocols in this type, or 0 if
5800  /// there are none.
5801  unsigned getNumProtocols() const {
5802  return static_cast<const T*>(this)->getNumProtocolsImpl();
5803  }
5804 
5805  /// Fetch a protocol by index.
5806  ObjCProtocolDecl *getProtocol(unsigned I) const {
5807  assert(I < getNumProtocols() && "Out-of-range protocol access");
5808  return qual_begin()[I];
5809  }
5810 
5811  /// Retrieve all of the protocol qualifiers.
5812  ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> getProtocols() const {
5813  return ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *>(qual_begin(), getNumProtocols());
5814  }
5815 };

5834 
5835  /// Return the number of qualifying protocols in this interface type,
5836  /// or 0 if there are none.

5839  }
5840 
5841  void setNumProtocolsImpl(unsigned N) {

5843  }
5844 
5845  ObjCTypeParamType(const ObjCTypeParamDecl *D,

5866 /// Represents a class type in Objective C.
5867 ///
5868 /// Every Objective C type is a combination of a base type, a set of
5869 /// type arguments (optional, for parameterized classes) and a list of
5870 /// protocols.
5871 ///
5872 /// Given the following declarations:
5873 /// \code
5874 /// \@class C<T>;
5875 /// \@protocol P;
5876 /// \endcode
5877 ///
5878 /// 'C' is an ObjCInterfaceType C. It is sugar for an ObjCObjectType
5879 /// with base C and no protocols.
5880 ///
5881 /// 'C<P>' is an unspecialized ObjCObjectType with base C and protocol list [P].
5882 /// 'C<C*>' is a specialized ObjCObjectType with type arguments 'C*' and no
5883 /// protocol list.
5884 /// 'C<C*><P>' is a specialized ObjCObjectType with base C, type arguments 'C*',
5885 /// and protocol list [P].
5886 ///
5887 /// 'id' is a TypedefType which is sugar for an ObjCObjectPointerType whose
5888 /// pointee is an ObjCObjectType with base BuiltinType::ObjCIdType
5889 /// and no protocols.
5890 ///
5891 /// 'id<P>' is an ObjCObjectPointerType whose pointee is an ObjCObjectType
5892 /// with base BuiltinType::ObjCIdType and protocol list [P]. Eventually
5893 /// this should get its own sugar class to better represent the source.
5894 class ObjCObjectType : public Type,
5895  public ObjCProtocolQualifiers<ObjCObjectType> {
5896  friend class ObjCProtocolQualifiers<ObjCObjectType>;
5897 
5898  // ObjCObjectType.NumTypeArgs - the number of type arguments stored
5899  // after the ObjCObjectPointerType node.
5900  // ObjCObjectType.NumProtocols - the number of protocols stored
5901  // after the type arguments of ObjCObjectPointerType node.
5902  //
5903  // These protocols are those written directly on the type. If
5904  // protocol qualifiers ever become additive, the iterators will need
5905  // to get kindof complicated.
5906  //
5907  // In the canonical object type, these are sorted alphabetically
5908  // and uniqued.
5909 
5910  /// Either a BuiltinType or an InterfaceType or sugar for either.
5911  QualType BaseType;
5912 
5913  /// Cached superclass type.
5914  mutable llvm::PointerIntPair<const ObjCObjectType *, 1, bool>
5915  CachedSuperClassType;
5916 
5917  QualType *getTypeArgStorage();
5918  const QualType *getTypeArgStorage() const {
5919  return const_cast<ObjCObjectType *>(this)->getTypeArgStorage();
5920  }
5921 
5922  ObjCProtocolDecl **getProtocolStorageImpl();
5923  /// Return the number of qualifying protocols in this interface type,
5924  /// or 0 if there are none.
5925  unsigned getNumProtocolsImpl() const {
5926  return ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumProtocols;
5927  }
5928  void setNumProtocolsImpl(unsigned N) {
5929  ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumProtocols = N;
5930  }
5931 
5932 protected:
5933  enum Nonce_ObjCInterface { Nonce_ObjCInterface };
5934 
5935  ObjCObjectType(QualType Canonical, QualType Base,
5936  ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs,
5937  ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols,
5938  bool isKindOf);
5939 
5940  ObjCObjectType(enum Nonce_ObjCInterface)
5941  : Type(ObjCInterface, QualType(), TypeDependence::None),
5942  BaseType(QualType(this_(), 0)) {
5943  ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumProtocols = 0;
5944  ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumTypeArgs = 0;
5945  ObjCObjectTypeBits.IsKindOf = 0;
5946  }
5947 
5948  void computeSuperClassTypeSlow() const;
5949 
5950 public:
5951  /// Gets the base type of this object type. This is always (possibly
5952  /// sugar for) one of:
5953  /// - the 'id' builtin type (as opposed to the 'id' type visible to the
5954  /// user, which is a typedef for an ObjCObjectPointerType)
5955  /// - the 'Class' builtin type (same caveat)
5956  /// - an ObjCObjectType (currently always an ObjCInterfaceType)
5957  QualType getBaseType() const { return BaseType; }
5958 
5959  bool isObjCId() const {
5960  return getBaseType()->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::ObjCId);
5961  }
5962 
5963  bool isObjCClass() const {
5964  return getBaseType()->isSpecificBuiltinType(BuiltinType::ObjCClass);
5965  }
5966 
5967  bool isObjCUnqualifiedId() const { return qual_empty() && isObjCId(); }
5968  bool isObjCUnqualifiedClass() const { return qual_empty() && isObjCClass(); }
5969  bool isObjCUnqualifiedIdOrClass() const {
5970  if (!qual_empty()) return false;
5971  if (const BuiltinType *T = getBaseType()->getAs<BuiltinType>())
5972  return T->getKind() == BuiltinType::ObjCId ||
5973  T->getKind() == BuiltinType::ObjCClass;
5974  return false;
5975  }
5976  bool isObjCQualifiedId() const { return !qual_empty() && isObjCId(); }
5977  bool isObjCQualifiedClass() const { return !qual_empty() && isObjCClass(); }
5978 
5979  /// Gets the interface declaration for this object type, if the base type
5980  /// really is an interface.
5981  ObjCInterfaceDecl *getInterface() const;
5982 
5983  /// Determine whether this object type is "specialized", meaning
5984  /// that it has type arguments.
5985  bool isSpecialized() const;
5986 
5987  /// Determine whether this object type was written with type arguments.
5988  bool isSpecializedAsWritten() const {
5989  return ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumTypeArgs > 0;
5990  }
5991 
5992  /// Determine whether this object type is "unspecialized", meaning
5993  /// that it has no type arguments.
5994  bool isUnspecialized() const { return !isSpecialized(); }
5995 
5996  /// Determine whether this object type is "unspecialized" as
5997  /// written, meaning that it has no type arguments.
5998  bool isUnspecializedAsWritten() const { return !isSpecializedAsWritten(); }
5999 
6000  /// Retrieve the type arguments of this object type (semantically).
6001  ArrayRef<QualType> getTypeArgs() const;
6002 
6003  /// Retrieve the type arguments of this object type as they were
6004  /// written.
6005  ArrayRef<QualType> getTypeArgsAsWritten() const {
6006  return llvm::makeArrayRef(getTypeArgStorage(),
6007  ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumTypeArgs);
6008  }
6009 
6010  /// Whether this is a "__kindof" type as written.
6011  bool isKindOfTypeAsWritten() const { return ObjCObjectTypeBits.IsKindOf; }
6012 
6013  /// Whether this ia a "__kindof" type (semantically).
6014  bool isKindOfType() const;
6015 
6016  /// Retrieve the type of the superclass of this object type.
6017  ///
6018  /// This operation substitutes any type arguments into the
6019  /// superclass of the current class type, potentially producing a
6020  /// specialization of the superclass type. Produces a null type if
6021  /// there is no superclass.
6022  QualType getSuperClassType() const {
6023  if (!CachedSuperClassType.getInt())
6024  computeSuperClassTypeSlow();
6025 
6026  assert(CachedSuperClassType.getInt() && "Superclass not set?");
6027  return QualType(CachedSuperClassType.getPointer(), 0);
6028  }
6029 
6030  /// Strip off the Objective-C "kindof" type and (with it) any
6031  /// protocol qualifiers.
6032  QualType stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(const ASTContext &ctx) const;
6033 
6034  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
6035  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
6036 
6037  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
6038  return T->getTypeClass() == ObjCObject ||
6039  T->getTypeClass() == ObjCInterface;
6040  }
6041 };

6043 /// A class providing a concrete implementation
6044 /// of ObjCObjectType, so as to not increase the footprint of
6045 /// ObjCInterfaceType. Code outside of ASTContext and the core type
6046 /// system should not reference this type.
6047 class ObjCObjectTypeImpl : public ObjCObjectType, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
6048  friend class ASTContext;
6049 
6050  // If anyone adds fields here, ObjCObjectType::getProtocolStorage()
6051  // will need to be modified.
6052 
6053  ObjCObjectTypeImpl(QualType Canonical, QualType Base,
6054  ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs,
6055  ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols,
6056  bool isKindOf)
6057  : ObjCObjectType(Canonical, Base, typeArgs, protocols, isKindOf) {}
6058 
6059 public:
6060  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID);
6061  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID,
6062  QualType Base,
6063  ArrayRef<QualType> typeArgs,
6064  ArrayRef<ObjCProtocolDecl *> protocols,
6065  bool isKindOf);

6068 inline QualType *ObjCObjectType::getTypeArgStorage() {
6069  return reinterpret_cast<QualType *>(static_cast<ObjCObjectTypeImpl*>(this)+1);
6070 }

6072 inline ObjCProtocolDecl **ObjCObjectType::getProtocolStorageImpl() {
6073  return reinterpret_cast<ObjCProtocolDecl**>(
6074  getTypeArgStorage() + ObjCObjectTypeBits.NumTypeArgs);
6075 }

6077 inline ObjCProtocolDecl **ObjCTypeParamType::getProtocolStorageImpl() {
6078  return reinterpret_cast<ObjCProtocolDecl**>(
6079  static_cast<ObjCTypeParamType*>(this)+1);
6080 }

6082 /// Interfaces are the core concept in Objective-C for object oriented design.
6083 /// They basically correspond to C++ classes. There are two kinds of interface
6084 /// types: normal interfaces like `NSString`, and qualified interfaces, which
6085 /// are qualified with a protocol list like `NSString<NSCopyable, NSAmazing>`.
6086 ///
6087 /// ObjCInterfaceType guarantees the following properties when considered
6088 /// as a subtype of its superclass, ObjCObjectType:
6089 /// - There are no protocol qualifiers. To reinforce this, code which
6090 /// tries to invoke the protocol methods via an ObjCInterfaceType will
6091 /// fail to compile.
6092 /// - It is its own base type. That is, if T is an ObjCInterfaceType*,
6093 /// T->getBaseType() == QualType(T, 0).
6094 class ObjCInterfaceType : public ObjCObjectType {
6095  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
6096  friend class ASTReader;
6097  template <class T> friend class serialization::AbstractTypeReader;
6098 
6099  ObjCInterfaceDecl *Decl;
6100 
6101  ObjCInterfaceType(const ObjCInterfaceDecl *D)
6102  : ObjCObjectType(Nonce_ObjCInterface),
6103  Decl(const_cast<ObjCInterfaceDecl*>(D)) {}
6104 
6105 public:
6106  /// Get the declaration of this interface.
6107  ObjCInterfaceDecl *getDecl() const;
6108 
6109  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
6110  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
6111 
6112  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
6113  return T->getTypeClass() == ObjCInterface;
6114  }
6115 
6116  // Nonsense to "hide" certain members of ObjCObjectType within this
6117  // class. People asking for protocols on an ObjCInterfaceType are
6118  // not going to get what they want: ObjCInterfaceTypes are
6119  // guaranteed to have no protocols.
6120  enum {
6121  qual_iterator,
6122  qual_begin,
6123  qual_end,
6124  getNumProtocols,
6125  getProtocol
6126  };
6127 };
6128 
6129 inline ObjCInterfaceDecl *ObjCObjectType::getInterface() const {
6130  QualType baseType = getBaseType();
6131  while (const auto *ObjT = baseType->getAs<ObjCObjectType>()) {
6132  if (const auto *T = dyn_cast<ObjCInterfaceType>(ObjT))
6133  return T->getDecl();
6134 
6135  baseType = ObjT->getBaseType();
6136  }
6137 
6138  return nullptr;
6139 }

6141 /// Represents a pointer to an Objective C object.
6142 ///
6143 /// These are constructed from pointer declarators when the pointee type is
6144 /// an ObjCObjectType (or sugar for one). In addition, the 'id' and 'Class'
6145 /// types are typedefs for these, and the protocol-qualified types 'id<P>'
6146 /// and 'Class<P>' are translated into these.
6147 ///
6148 /// Pointers to pointers to Objective C objects are still PointerTypes;
6149 /// only the first level of pointer gets it own type implementation.
6150 class ObjCObjectPointerType : public Type, public llvm::FoldingSetNode {
6151  friend class ASTContext; // ASTContext creates these.
6152 
6153  QualType PointeeType;
6154 
6155  ObjCObjectPointerType(QualType Canonical, QualType Pointee)
6156  : Type(ObjCObjectPointer, Canonical, Pointee->getDependence()),
6157  PointeeType(Pointee) {}
6158 
6159 public:
6160  /// Gets the type pointed to by this ObjC pointer.
6161  /// The result will always be an ObjCObjectType or sugar thereof.
6162  QualType getPointeeType() const { return PointeeType; }
6163 
6164  /// Gets the type pointed to by this ObjC pointer. Always returns non-null.
6165  ///
6166  /// This method is equivalent to getPointeeType() except that
6167  /// it discards any typedefs (or other sugar) between this
6168  /// type and the "outermost" object type. So for:
6169  /// \code
6170  /// \@class A; \@protocol P; \@protocol Q;
6171  /// typedef A<P> AP;
6172  /// typedef A A1;
6173  /// typedef A1<P> A1P;
6174  /// typedef A1P<Q> A1PQ;
6175  /// \endcode
6176  /// For 'A*', getObjectType() will return 'A'.
6177  /// For 'A<P>*', getObjectType() will return 'A<P>'.
6178  /// For 'AP*', getObjectType() will return 'A<P>'.
6179  /// For 'A1*', getObjectType() will return 'A'.
6180  /// For 'A1<P>*', getObjectType() will return 'A1<P>'.
6181  /// For 'A1P*', getObjectType() will return 'A1<P>'.
6182  /// For 'A1PQ*', getObjectType() will return 'A1<Q>', because
6183  /// adding protocols to a protocol-qualified base discards the
6184  /// old qualifiers (for now). But if it didn't, getObjectType()
6185  /// would return 'A1P<Q>' (and we'd have to make iterating over
6186  /// qualifiers more complicated).
6187  const ObjCObjectType *getObjectType() const {
6188  return PointeeType->castAs<ObjCObjectType>();
6189  }
6190 
6191  /// If this pointer points to an Objective C
6192  /// \@interface type, gets the type for that interface. Any protocol
6193  /// qualifiers on the interface are ignored.
6194  ///
6195  /// \return null if the base type for this pointer is 'id' or 'Class'
6196  const ObjCInterfaceType *getInterfaceType() const;
6197 
6198  /// If this pointer points to an Objective \@interface
6199  /// type, gets the declaration for that interface.
6200  ///
6201  /// \return null if the base type for this pointer is 'id' or 'Class'
6202  ObjCInterfaceDecl *getInterfaceDecl() const {
6203  return getObjectType()->getInterface();
6204  }
6205 
6206  /// True if this is equivalent to the 'id' type, i.e. if
6207  /// its object type is the primitive 'id' type with no protocols.
6208  bool isObjCIdType() const {
6209  return getObjectType()->isObjCUnqualifiedId();
6210  }
6211 
6212  /// True if this is equivalent to the 'Class' type,
6213  /// i.e. if its object tive is the primitive 'Class' type with no protocols.
6214  bool isObjCClassType() const {
6215  return getObjectType()->isObjCUnqualifiedClass();
6216  }
6217 
6218  /// True if this is equivalent to the 'id' or 'Class' type,
6219  bool isObjCIdOrClassType() const {
6220  return getObjectType()->isObjCUnqualifiedIdOrClass();
6221  }
6222 
6223  /// True if this is equivalent to 'id<P>' for some non-empty set of
6224  /// protocols.
6225  bool isObjCQualifiedIdType() const {
6226  return getObjectType()->isObjCQualifiedId();
6227  }
6228 
6229  /// True if this is equivalent to 'Class<P>' for some non-empty set of
6230  /// protocols.
6231  bool isObjCQualifiedClassType() const {
6232  return getObjectType()->isObjCQualifiedClass();
6233  }
6234 
6235  /// Whether this is a "__kindof" type.
6236  bool isKindOfType() const { return getObjectType()->isKindOfType(); }
6237 
6238  /// Whether this type is specialized, meaning that it has type arguments.
6239  bool isSpecialized() const { return getObjectType()->isSpecialized(); }
6240 
6241  /// Whether this type is specialized, meaning that it has type arguments.
6242  bool isSpecializedAsWritten() const {
6243  return getObjectType()->isSpecializedAsWritten();
6244  }
6245 
6246  /// Whether this type is unspecialized, meaning that is has no type arguments.
6247  bool isUnspecialized() const { return getObjectType()->isUnspecialized(); }
6248 
6249  /// Determine whether this object type is "unspecialized" as
6250  /// written, meaning that it has no type arguments.
6251  bool isUnspecializedAsWritten() const { return !isSpecializedAsWritten(); }
6252 
6253  /// Retrieve the type arguments for this type.
6254  ArrayRef<QualType> getTypeArgs() const {
6255  return getObjectType()->getTypeArgs();
6256  }
6257 
6258  /// Retrieve the type arguments for this type.
6259  ArrayRef<QualType> getTypeArgsAsWritten() const {
6260  return getObjectType()->getTypeArgsAsWritten();
6261  }
6262 
6263  /// An iterator over the qualifiers on the object type. Provided
6264  /// for convenience. This will always iterate over the full set of
6265  /// protocols on a type, not just those provided directly.
6266  using qual_iterator = ObjCObjectType::qual_iterator;
6267  using qual_range = llvm::iterator_range<qual_iterator>;
6268 
6269  qual_range quals() const { return qual_range(qual_begin(), qual_end()); }
6270 
6271  qual_iterator qual_begin() const {
6272  return getObjectType()->qual_begin();
6273  }
6274 
6275  qual_iterator qual_end() const {
6276  return getObjectType()->qual_end();
6277  }
6278 
6279  bool qual_empty() const { return getObjectType()->qual_empty(); }
6280 
6281  /// Return the number of qualifying protocols on the object type.
6282  unsigned getNumProtocols() const {
6283  return getObjectType()->getNumProtocols();
6284  }
6285 
6286  /// Retrieve a qualifying protocol by index on the object type.
6287  ObjCProtocolDecl *getProtocol(unsigned I) const {
6288  return getObjectType()->getProtocol(I);
6289  }
6290 
6291  bool isSugared() const { return false; }
6292  QualType desugar() const { return QualType(this, 0); }
6293 
6294  /// Retrieve the type of the superclass of this object pointer type.
6295  ///
6296  /// This operation substitutes any type arguments into the
6297  /// superclass of the current class type, potentially producing a
6298  /// pointer to a specialization of the superclass type. Produces a
6299  /// null type if there is no superclass.
6300  QualType getSuperClassType() const;
6301 
6302  /// Strip off the Objective-C "kindof" type and (with it) any
6303  /// protocol qualifiers.
6304  const ObjCObjectPointerType *stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(
6305  const ASTContext &ctx) const;
6306 
6307  void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID) {
6308  Profile(ID, getPointeeType());
6309  }
6310 
6311  static void Profile(llvm::FoldingSetNodeID &ID, QualType T) {
6312  ID.AddPointer(T.getAsOpaquePtr());
6313  }
6314 
6315  static bool classof(const Type *T) {
6316  return T->getTypeClass() == ObjCObjectPointer;
6317  }
6318 };

6440 
6441 /// A qualifier set is used to build a set of qualifiers.
6442 class QualifierCollector : public Qualifiers {
6443 public:
6444  QualifierCollector(Qualifiers Qs = Qualifiers()) : Qualifiers(Qs) {}
6445 
6446  /// Collect any qualifiers on the given type and return an
6447  /// unqualified type. The qualifiers are assumed to be consistent
6448  /// with those already in the type.
6449  const Type *strip(QualType type) {
6450  addFastQualifiers(type.getLocalFastQualifiers());
6451  if (!type.hasLocalNonFastQualifiers())
6452  return type.getTypePtrUnsafe();
6453 
6454  const ExtQuals *extQuals = type.getExtQualsUnsafe();
6455  addConsistentQualifiers(extQuals->getQualifiers());
6456  return extQuals->getBaseType();
6457  }
6458 
6459  /// Apply the collected qualifiers to the given type.
6460  QualType apply(const ASTContext &Context, QualType QT) const;
6461 
6462  /// Apply the collected qualifiers to the given type.
6463  QualType apply(const ASTContext &Context, const Type* T) const;
6464 };

6466 /// A container of type source information.
6467 ///
6468 /// A client can read the relevant info using TypeLoc wrappers, e.g:
6469 /// @code
6470 /// TypeLoc TL = TypeSourceInfo->getTypeLoc();
6471 /// TL.getBeginLoc().print(OS, SrcMgr);
6472 /// @endcode
6473 class alignas(8) TypeSourceInfo {
6474  // Contains a memory block after the class, used for type source information,
6475  // allocated by ASTContext.
6476  friend class ASTContext;
6477 
6478  QualType Ty;
6479 
6480  TypeSourceInfo(QualType ty) : Ty(ty) {}
6481 
6482 public:
6483  /// Return the type wrapped by this type source info.
6484  QualType getType() const { return Ty; }
6485 
6486  /// Return the TypeLoc wrapper for the type source info.
6487  TypeLoc getTypeLoc() const; // implemented in TypeLoc.h
6488 
6489  /// Override the type stored in this TypeSourceInfo. Use with caution!
6490  void overrideType(QualType T) { Ty = T; }
6491 };

6495 inline SplitQualType SplitQualType::getSingleStepDesugaredType() const {
6496  SplitQualType desugar =
6497  Ty->getLocallyUnqualifiedSingleStepDesugaredType().split();
6498  desugar.Quals.addConsistentQualifiers(Quals);

6502 inline const Type *QualType::getTypePtr() const {
6503  return getCommonPtr()->BaseType;
6504 }

6507  return (isNull() ? nullptr : getCommonPtr()->BaseType);
6508 }

6510 inline SplitQualType QualType::split() const {
6511  if (!hasLocalNonFastQualifiers())
6512  return SplitQualType(getTypePtrUnsafe(),
6513  Qualifiers::fromFastMask(getLocalFastQualifiers()));
6514 
6515  const ExtQuals *eq = getExtQualsUnsafe();
6516  Qualifiers qs = eq->getQualifiers();
6517  qs.addFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
6518  return SplitQualType(eq->getBaseType(), qs);
6519 }
6520 
6521 inline Qualifiers QualType::getLocalQualifiers() const {
6522  Qualifiers Quals;
6523  if (hasLocalNonFastQualifiers())
6524  Quals = getExtQualsUnsafe()->getQualifiers();
6525  Quals.addFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
6526  return Quals;
6527 }
6528 
6529 inline Qualifiers QualType::getQualifiers() const {
6530  Qualifiers quals = getCommonPtr()->CanonicalType.getLocalQualifiers();
6531  quals.addFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
6532  return quals;
6533 }

6535 inline unsigned QualType::getCVRQualifiers() const {
6536  unsigned cvr = getCommonPtr()->CanonicalType.getLocalCVRQualifiers();
6537  cvr |= getLocalCVRQualifiers();
6538  return cvr;
6539 }

6550 inline bool QualType::isCanonicalAsParam() const {
6551  if (!isCanonical()) return false;
6552  if (hasLocalQualifiers()) return false;
6553 
6554  const Type *T = getTypePtr();
6555  if (T->isVariablyModifiedType() && T->hasSizedVLAType())
6556  return false;
6557 
6558  return !isa<FunctionType>(T) && !isa<ArrayType>(T);
6559 }

6608 inline void QualType::removeLocalCVRQualifiers(unsigned Mask) {
6609  assert(!(Mask & ~Qualifiers::CVRMask) && "mask has non-CVR bits");
6610  static_assert((int)Qualifiers::CVRMask == (int)Qualifiers::FastMask,
6611  "Fast bits differ from CVR bits!");
6612 
6613  // Fast path: we don't need to touch the slow qualifiers.
6614  removeLocalFastQualifiers(Mask);
6615 }

6650 inline FunctionType::ExtInfo getFunctionExtInfo(const Type &t) {
6651  if (const auto *PT = t.getAs<PointerType>()) {
6652  if (const auto *FT = PT->getPointeeType()->getAs<FunctionType>())
6653  return FT->getExtInfo();

6655  return FT->getExtInfo();

6664 /// Determine whether this type is more
6665 /// qualified than the Other type. For example, "const volatile int"
6666 /// is more qualified than "const int", "volatile int", and
6667 /// "int". However, it is not more qualified than "const volatile
6668 /// int".
6669 inline bool QualType::isMoreQualifiedThan(QualType other) const {
6670  Qualifiers MyQuals = getQualifiers();
6671  Qualifiers OtherQuals = other.getQualifiers();
6672  return (MyQuals != OtherQuals && MyQuals.compatiblyIncludes(OtherQuals));
6673 }
6674 
6675 /// Determine whether this type is at last
6676 /// as qualified as the Other type. For example, "const volatile
6677 /// int" is at least as qualified as "const int", "volatile int",
6678 /// "int", and "const volatile int".
6679 inline bool QualType::isAtLeastAsQualifiedAs(QualType other) const {
6680  Qualifiers OtherQuals = other.getQualifiers();
6681 
6682  // Ignore __unaligned qualifier if this type is a void.
6683  if (getUnqualifiedType()->isVoidType())
6684  OtherQuals.removeUnaligned();
6685 
6686  return getQualifiers().compatiblyIncludes(OtherQuals);
6687 }
6688 
6689 /// If Type is a reference type (e.g., const
6690 /// int&), returns the type that the reference refers to ("const
6691 /// int"). Otherwise, returns the type itself. This routine is used
6692 /// throughout Sema to implement C++ 5p6:
6693 ///
6694 /// If an expression initially has the type "reference to T" (8.3.2,
6695 /// 8.5.3), the type is adjusted to "T" prior to any further
6696 /// analysis, the expression designates the object or function
6697 /// denoted by the reference, and the expression is an lvalue.
6698 inline QualType QualType::getNonReferenceType() const {
6699  if (const auto *RefType = (*this)->getAs<ReferenceType>())
6700  return RefType->getPointeeType();
6701  else
6702  return *this;
6703 }
6704 
6705 inline bool QualType::isCForbiddenLValueType() const {
6706  return ((getTypePtr()->isVoidType() && !hasQualifiers()) ||
6707  getTypePtr()->isFunctionType());
6708 }
